<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Confirms It May Send War Planes Abroad for War Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese military official
confirmed to the press today that Japan's Air Self-Defense Force
may send a main battle fighter jet force equipped with F-15 jet
fighters abroad for a multinational war game and inflight
refueling training next year.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese forces can exercise all-dimensional actual combat
in the joint war game in Alaska and the United States, without the
restriction of narrow air space as in Japan, said Muragi Koji,
chief of staff of Japan's Air Self-Defense Force.
</P>
<P>
The war game, which will involve U.S., British and Canadian air
forces, is held four times a year and was started by the United
States in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo Shimbun reported last Sunday that it will be
unprecedented for Japan's Air Self-Defense Force to participate in
a military exercise and inflight refueling training abroad.
</P>
<P>
The F-15 jet fighters, which can fly at most 4,600 kilometers
in the air without refueling, will practice inflight refueling
with U.S. refueling planes on the 7,000-kilometer-long way to
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Air Self-Defense Force started to dispatch
researchers to watch the exercise in 1992. In 1996, Japan sent
two C-130 transport planes and surface-to-air missiles to
participate in the exercise.
</P>
<P>
On June 9-20, the Japanese Air Self-Defense Force participated
in the exercise in the same scale.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Shimbun commented that as a country pursuing a
national policy of pure defense, Japan has always been strict in
sending war planes abroad.
</P>
<P>
On inflight refueling training, former Japanese Prime Minister
Kakuei Tanaka pointed out in 1973 that "Japan does not possess
inflight refueling planes, nor does it participate in inflight
training or exercises."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Social Party, the predecessor of the present
Social Democratic Party, then also strongly opposed inflight
refueling training, holding that "inflight refueling extends the
time combat planes can stay in the air, enhancing aviation ability
and imposing greater threat to neighboring countries."
</P>
<P>
The opposition forced the Japanese Air Self-Defense Force to
remove the inflight refueling devices from its F-4 jet fighters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
