<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Foreign Currency Reserves Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's foreign currency
reserves have risen to cover five months import over the past two
months, dealers said on today.
</P>
<P>
When the tobacco auction season opened in April, a month later
the reserves had improved to cover four months import.
</P>
<P>
In separate interviews with the Zimbabwe News Agency, dealers
said five months import cover was quite sufficient bearing in
mind that the Central Bank considered four months import cover
sufficient to cope with demand.
</P>
<P>
Normally when floors opened, reserves would rise to about five
to six months' import cover, and this was expected as the season
continued.
</P>
<P>
''Now that sales for this season's tobacco have been reviewed
due to reduced yields, this is not going to have any negative
impact on foreign reserves, as four months cover has always been
enough to sustain the market,'' said one dealer.
</P>
<P>
This year's tobacco sales had been revised to 196,000 tons
from 214,000 tons due to reduced yields resulting from excessive
rains.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that at the moment there is pressure on the
exchange rate resulting in few buyers on the market, especially
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
''In two months time we should expect depreciation pressure of
local currency against the U.S. Dollar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the large buying on the market by importers
early this month after news of a possible devaluation of the
local currency by five percent by the end of the year had
settled, after the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe started selling hard
currency to the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
