<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Honors Famous Physicist Wu Youxun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A gathering was held in Beijing
this morning to mark the 100th anniversary of the birth of a
famous Chinese physicist Prof. Wu Youxun.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, Liu Huaqing, a member of the Standing
Committee of the Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party
Central Committee, called on noted figures in China's scientific
and technological world to learn from Wu's patriotism and fulfill
the strategy of invigorating the country through science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Wu (1897-1977) was one of the pioneers of modern physics
in China, as well as one of the founding fathers of the Chinese
Physics Society. He also served as vice-president of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Wu's scientific achievements were mainly for the confirming the
theory of "Compton Effects" produced by electromagnetic radiation
in fields of x-rays and gamma rays. The theory was initiated and
developed by Dr. Arthur H. Compton, who won the Nobel Prize in
1927.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Chen Ning Yang, a Chinese-American scientist who won the
Nobel prize in physics in 1957, recalled the days when he studied
physics under Wu.
</P>
<P>
"Today's meeting has shown that the Chinese government attaches
importance to anyone who has contributed to China's scientific and
educational causes," Yang noted.
</P>
<P>
Wang Dazhong, president of Qinghua University, spoke highly of
Wu's teaching style, saying that "we will try to turn Qinghua into
one of the world's top universities in the next century, and train
more first-class talents for our country."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
