<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Seventh Wetland Under Ramsar Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The area of wetlands around Mai
Po and Inner Deep Bay in Hong Kong have become China's seventh
Wetland of International Importance under the Ramsar Convention.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the convention, every signatory country is
obliged to guarantee the wise use and conservation of its wetlands
in a bid to protect the rich fauna and flora that they support.
</P>
<P>
"It is a clear signal of China's long-term commitment to the
conservation of the area," said Dr. Lew Young, World Wide Fund For
Nature Hong Kong (WWF HK) Mai Po Reserve Manager.
</P>
<P>
He added that experience at the reserve has shown how wetlands
can be managed for the benefit of the community by providing a
valuable area for environmental education.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tianhou, WWF HK Training Officer, said that WWF has been
working closely with China's Ministry of Forestry, and that it
will enhance its cooperation with inland officials in charge of
wetland management.
</P>
<P>
Among China's six other Ramsar Sites are East Dongting Lake in
central-south China's Hunan Province, Poyang Lake in east China's
Jiangxi and Birds Islands in northwest China's Qinghai province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
