<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oil Industry Records Sustained Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- China's petroleum industry will
enjoy sustainable growth with the maximum annual oil production
probably reaching 200 million tons by the year 2010, according to
a senior Chinese oil official.
</P>
<P>
After 40 years of development, China now produces an annual oil
output of 157 million tons, retaining the status of the world's
fifth-largest oil producer.
</P>
<P>
The official told a press conference here today that China's
has achieved great success in "stabilizing the East while
developing the West and offshore" oil resources.
</P>
<P>
China has built 350 oilfields and 110 gasfields. It has also
set up 24 oil and gas producing bases including Daqing, Shengli,
Liaohe, Xinjiang, Sichuan, Dagang, Bohai, East South China Sea,
West South China Sea, and basically formed four major oil and
three major gas producing regions.
</P>
<P>
Among these, the oil output of Songliao region in 1996
accounted for 38 percent of the national total, contributing
greatly to the growth of the national economy. The production of
Bohai Bay in 1996 shared 36.9 percent of the national oil
output. Xinjiang produced 14.3 million tons of crude oil last
year, making up 9.1 percent of the national total. The offshore
production reached 15 million tons, accounting for 9.5 percent of
the country's total.
</P>
<P>
According to oil experts, the annual oil output of east China
will stay at around 110 million tons in 2010. The annual oil
output of 53 million tons at Daqing Oilfield will be maintained
until 2010.
</P>
<P>
The exploration will be further accelerated in the west and the
oil output may reach 40-50 million tons in 2010. Offshore oil
production is estimated at 10 million tons or more by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Up to late 1996, the total onshore areas open to foreign
companies reached 2.5 million sq km and 30 petroleum contracts
were signed with 35 foreign companies, involving a total of 770
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
More than 110 offshore contracts have been signed with a
foreign capital of about three billion US dollars, which amounts
to 58 percent of the total investment of offshore oil exploration
and development for that period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
