<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Commissioner Concerned With Deadlock in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU)
Commissioner for External Relations, Hans Van den Broek, expressed
deep concern today with the deadlock of the peace process in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
On the outcome of the second round of U.N.-led direct talks
last week in Switzerland, Van den Broek said that the precondition
set by the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, implying the
freezing of an EU decision to start accession negotiations with
Cyprus in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
"This is unacceptable", he was quoted as saying in a statement
following a report to the U.N. Security Council by
U.N. Secretary-General's Special Advisor on Cyprus, Diego
Cordovez, according to Cyprus News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He reconfirmed that accession negotiations would be launched
by beginning of next year, as agreed by the EU in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Commissioner, who is responsible for relations with Cyprus
and Turkey, also criticized the signing of an "association
agreement" between Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot regime as not
being conducive to creating the right negotiating climate.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed a few days before last week's five-day
direct talks between President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Denktash in Switzerland, calls for the partial
integration of the Turkish-controlled northern Cyprus with Turkey
if the EU accession negotiations go ahead with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot communities' leaders held first round of
face-to-face negotiations in the U.S. in July.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek underlined that a window of opportunity now
exists to build a framework for a mediated settlement to the
protracted Cyprus problem before the start of accession talks,
noting that Cyprus' adhesion to the EU would be in the interest
of both communities on the island.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that attempts to frustrate any progress, even
of a procedural nature as demonstrated last week in Switzerland,
are detrimental to the whole population of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU official recalled the recent pledge by the
Turkish government to play a constructive role in the search for a
negotiated Cyprus solution, stressing that such a role would also
favor the deepening of the relations between the EU and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek strongly urged the two parties in Cyprus to
reach an early agreement on the continuation of direct talks and
pledged the European Commission's full support for further
efforts to be undertaken by the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkey sent troops and took over the
northern third in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lack of Will Hampers African Labor Integration: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
harare, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The lack of political will,
varying degrees of economic development and different labor laws
in African countries were seen as some of the major obstacles to
regional labor market integration, according to a seminar today.
</P>
<P>
The five-day Seminar on Regional Integration and Labor
Administration, which concluded here today, reached this
conclusion in its resolutions passed at the end of the seminar.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, attended by more than 40 delegates from a number
of African countries, said in the resolutions, "it was realized
that there is mutual suspicion by individual countries of the
erosion of national sovereignty and inherent fear that bigger
economies stand to gain immensely at the expense of weaker
countries."
</P>
<P>
On the economic obstacles, the participants said
non-liberalization of regional trade contributed to current
limitations that made labor integration difficult.
</P>
<P>
Another problem noted by participants was multiplicity of
economic groupings advancing similar ideals which resulted in
overlapping jurisdiction and divided loyalties among members.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, however, also outlined the positive aspects of
labor integration covering economic growth and greater job
opportunities resulting in improved living standards.
</P>
<P>
It was also recommended that the African Regional Labor
Administration Center could play an important role in addressing
training needs of the labor force on how to deal with effects of
structural adjustment.
</P>
<P>
Recommendations from the workshop were expected to be
submitted to all African labor ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
