<HEADLINE> Denmark to Fund Southern African Peace-keeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and Denmark today
signed a 2.3 million U.S. Dollars agreement which will fund the
Southern African regional peace-keeping training center.
</P>
<P>
The money would be used to build infrastructure at the
Zimbabwe military staff college which houses the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) regional center for peace-keeping
studies, and develop training programs.
</P>
<P>
Senior Secretary of the Zimbabwean Finance Ministry Charles
Kuwaza said the choice of the staff college as the center for
peace-keeping studies was in recognition of the role of
Zimbabwe's Defense Forces in international peace-keeping
missions.
</P>
<P>
Acting Danish Ambassador to Zimbabwe Ib Petersen said SADC
countries had shown commitment to enhancing the peace and
economic growth the region was currently enjoying by establishing
the peace training center.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaza signed the agreement on behalf of Zimbabwe while
Petersen signed on behalf of Denmark. 
</P>
