<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Papers Shut Down in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Two leading independent
newspapers in Sierra Leone said today they are suspending their
publications with immediate effect "due to insecurity."
</P>
<P>
The two biweeklies, Standard Times and the Vision now join a
chain of nine other papers off the streets since the military
seized power on May 25.
</P>
<P>
The nine include the Punch, For Di People, the Democrat, New
Tablet, Freedom Now, Unity Now and The Sierra Leonean.
</P>
<P>
The editors claimed "harassment by security officials" as the
main cause of their decision to shut down.
</P>
<P>
The editor of Standard Times, Philip Neville said in an
interview, "I decided to suspend publication because I was
virtually haunted by fierce looking men at night. They will knock
on my door and smear paint on my windows."
</P>
<P>
Neville was beaten up three days after the coup by uniformed
men and so far nobody has been caught.
</P>
<P>
The editor of Unity Now, Frank Kposowa had to go underground
when security officials stormed his office three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Kposowa, who is the president of the Sierra Leone Association
of Journalists, only surfaced after junta officials promised he
would not be harmed.
</P>
<P>
Other journalists including the correspondent for the Voice of
America, Kelvin Lewis and BBC correspondent Victor Sylver were
briefly detained in recent weeks by the regime without
explanation.
</P>
<P>
Many journalists have fled to neighboring Guinea and Gambia.
Over 30 Sierra Leonean journalists in Guinea have now formed the
Sierra Leone Journalist Association in exile.
</P>
<P>
Only eight out of the 52 newspapers existing under the
civilian government continue to publish. They include the
government-owned Daily Mail, Expo Times, both with strong
leanings to the junta, and independent publications like Concord
Times, the Point, The Pool, Torchlight, Herald Guardian and We
Yone.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner of Information and Broadcasting, Sedu Turay
said the editors are just blaming the government for their own
shortcomings. Journalists must keep in mind they should know that
they should be responsible for what they are reporting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
