<HEADLINE> Feature Film to Be Shot in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A feature film of "To Walk With
The Lions" will be shot in Nairobi and the Shabba Game Reserve in
Kenya at a cost of 10 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The film is based on the story of the late George Adamson who
dedicated his whole life to the conservation of wildlife in the
east African country.
</P>
<P>
John Buchanan, executive producer of the film to be produced
by Canadian Kingsborough Greenlight Pictures Inc., was quoted as
saying that his company intended to import tame lions for the
exercise.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that a bill would soon be tabled in Kenya's
parliament in order to promote film-making industry in the
country.
</P>
<P>
If the bill passed, Kenya would establish a film commission
which is designed to promote Kenya as a film-making destination.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Information and Broadcasting Minister Johnstone Makau
said Kenya had taken various measures to make Kenya an attractive
film location when he received Buchanan on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
These measures include reduction of duty on filming equipment,
easing immigration regulations for artists and processing
application within a week.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that if the film-making industry in Kenya
boomed, the tourism industry, the biggest foreign exchange earner
of the country, will be the immediate beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
He said that the film "Out Of Africa" had led to a boom in the
tourism industry in the mid-1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
