<HEADLINE> ECOMOG to Check Armed Robbery in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force in Liberia, known as ECOMOG, said today it had intensified
security patrols in and around the capital Monrovia to check the
menace of armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
According to ECOMOG force commander Major-general Victor Malu,
this is part of the efforts his troops have perfected in
conjunction with other security agencies to combat the robbery
menace.
</P>
<P>
He assured that the new measures would soon start to yield
positive results.
</P>
<P>
According to the News Agency of Nigeria, Malu was trying to
allay the fears of Liberians over the persistent reports of armed
robbery incidents, which he said was being exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to Liberians, especially the residents of
Monrovia, to assist the efforts of the security agencies to
tackle the rising wave of crimes in the country.
</P>
<P>
To maintain security is one of the most crucial tasks for
Liberia's new government in the course of national reconstruction
after seven years of bloody civil war.
</P>
<P>
The first bill signed into law by President Charles Taylor
charges ECOMOG, which has helped bring the country back into
normalcy, with the responsibility to maintain security.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed in Abuja, Nigeria, by Liberia's
factional leaders a year ago, ECOMOG will help restructure the
Liberian army and police force in six months after the new
government was installed on August 2.
</P>
<P>
The stay of ECOMOG, however, may be extended because the
training of the forces has not begun.
</P>
<P>
The summit of west African leaders coming next Thursday is
expected to make decision on the forces' stay in Liberia.
</P>
</TEXT>
