<HEADLINE> Greek Parliament Speaker Meets U.S. Congressmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Greek Parliament President
Apostolos Kaklamanis today met with a visiting U.S. Congressmen
delegation on issues of Greek-Turkish relations and developments
in the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after their talks, Robert Menendez, who
is heading a delegation of members of the House of
Representatives' Foreign Relations Committee, expressed concern
over the Cyprus problem and the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
"we are concerned with the tensions in the Aegean and the
Cyprus issue, and are seeking a just and viable solution to the
Cyprus problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that Greece was "a very important ally" of the
U.S. and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thomas Niles, U.S. ambassador to Greece, said later
that the process which began in Madrid was alive and Washington
believed that progress would continue.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the U.S. had "a clear commitment" and would
work for a settlement of the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In July, Greece and Turkey signed a joint communique on the
sideline of the NATO summit meeting in Madrid, Spain, signaling
the start of the process in which the two countries try to better
their strained relations.
</P>
<P>
But recently, the signing of a partial integration pact between
Turkey and northern Cyprus as well as the failure of the second
round of direct talks between Cyprus' Greek and Turkish
communities have shadowed the process. 
</P>
