<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Demonstrators Protest Closure of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Around 2,000 demonstrators
gathered today at Beyazit Mosque in Istanbul, the largest city
of Turkey, to protest closure of religious schools.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported that the
demonstrators launched the protest following their Friday prayer
service, chanting anti-government slogans such as "The Islamic
development can not be prevented."
</P>
<P>
The conservative Islamists rally every Friday around mosques,
especially in Istanbul, since the Turkey government headed by
Mesut Yilmaz initiated the controversial eight-year compulsory
education reform bill on August 17.
</P>
<P>
They were enraged by the adoption of the bill in the
Parliament, which is believed to be a heavy blow to the
fundamentalists in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The authorities sent a large number of policemen to disperse
the demonstrators, but no clashes took place.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Murat Baseskioglu said Thursday that
evidence collected by his ministry shows that radical Islamic
groups are behind the recent regular Friday rallies to protest
the education reform plan, according to early reports.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Interior Ministry was determined to stop
such illegal demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the Yilmaz government initiated the
education law in order to curb the further expansion of the
fundamentalists in the secular country.
</P>
<P>
According to the new law, students have to finish eight years of
elementary education before they are permitted to start
religious studies. The law led to the closure of many religious
schools in Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
