<HEADLINE> White House Shifts Position on White Teacher's Dismissal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The White House told the
Supreme Court today that a white teacher was dismissed illegally
by a New Jersey school board seeking to promote racial diversity
by keeping an equally qualified black instructor.
</P>
<P>
But in a legal brief, the administration maintained its support
for the principle that affirmative action can be used to attain
racial diversity as well as to remedy past bias, as long as the
diversity serves a narrowly tailored compelling interest.
</P>
<P>
The brief argues that the board did not show a need for racial
diversity in a part of its faculty, the business education
department, particularly since its overall faculty was racially
diverse.
</P>
<P>
News reports quoted White House spokesman Barry Toiv as saying
from where President Bill Clinton is vacationing outside
Washington, "We think this case ought to be decided on narrow
grounds and the facts of the case and should not be used for
affirmative action."
</P>
<P>
But the brief said that if the court looks at the larger
question, then it should rule that an appeals court erred in
ruling that affirmative action could only be used to remedy past
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
The brief represents the third position taken by the government
during the Bush and Clinton administrations.
</P>
<P>
The Bush administration initially opposed the school board. In
1994 during President Clinton's first term, the government
switched sides and backed the school board.
</P>
<P>
Today, the Clinton administration completed a long process of
backing off that position while still arguing that affirmative
action can be used to promote racial diversity so long as it
provides demonstrable benefits.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration in June, apparently fearing the
Supreme Court would use the New Jersey reverse-bias case to
further restrict affirmative action, unsuccessfully urged the
justices to steer clear of the case altogether. That would have
let stand a lower court ruling against the school board.
</P>
<P>
The dispute dates back to the school board's 1989 decision to
abolish one teaching position in Piscataway High School's business
education department.
</P>
<P>
New Jersey law requires that tenured teachers be laid off in
reverse order of seniority, but two teachers -- Sharon Taxman and
Debra Williams -- had been hired on the same day nine years
earlier. The school board laid off Taxman, who is white, saying
that Williams, who is black, was the only minority teacher in the
10-teacher department.
</P>
<P>
Taxman filed a complaint with the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission and the Justice Department in President Bush's
administration, argued for her and against the school board,
saying her dismissal was an unlawful act of reverse
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
A federal judge agreed with her assertion that her dismissal
violated the 1964 Civil Rights Act. When the school board
appealed, the Clinton administration reversed the Bush
administration's stance, and directed Justice Department lawyers
to defend the school board.
</P>
<P>
After the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in 1996 also agreed
with Taxman, the Clinton administration decided to abandon the
court fight. But when the Supreme Court decided in June to take
the case, the administration left open the possibility it might
file a brief.
</P>
<P>
The court is expected to hear the case in its 1997-98 term
beginning this fall and is expected to render a decision next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
