<HEADLINE> IMF Disburses 21 Billion CFA Francs to Cameroun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has disbursed 21 billion CFA Francs (nearly 40 million U.S.
Dollars) to the government of Cameroun to finance its three-year
economic financial and social program, Radio Cameroun reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken on Wednesday night in Washington by the
IMF Board of Directors after signing the fifth standby accord of
economic cooperation with Cameroun.
</P>
<P>
According to Jean Gaukou, a senior official from the Ministry
of Economy and Finance of Cameroun, this fifth standby accord
goes a long way to re-establish Cameroun's credibility with the
international financial institutions and places Cameroun in a
better position to settle its debts.
</P>
<P>
The fifth standby accord is a financial aid mechanism between
the IMF and Cameroun, a loan scheme which seeks to prop economic
reform programs, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The accord is accompanied by a three-year middle term
financial and economic program which will take the nation into
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The program is based on a policy to promote a minimum annual
economic growth rate of 5 percent, contain inflation between 2 to
3 percent, and reduce poverty in the country, the radio added.
</P>
<P>
The program also aims at promoting social and economic welfare
by the creation of jobs, human and infrastructural development,
restructuring of the banking and the public sectors, improvement
of the institutional environment, and promotion of public and
private investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
