<HEADLINE> Korean Motor Plant Under Construction in Botswana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A Korea-designed Hyundai
motor company is under construction in Gaborone, Botswana, the
South African Press Association (SAPA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The 51.06 million U.S. Dollar car assembly plant is planned to
start full operation in April next year, 18 months ahead of
original schedule. The pilot production would begin in January,
informed sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The plant will have an initial capacity of 30,000 vehicles a
year. Production of 40,000 vehicles per annum is an early target,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
"We are planning for 30,000 units for export to South Africa
and 10,000 for the rest of the region," Director of the plant
Billy Rautenbach told a press conference in Gaborone.
</P>
<P>
The production of Hyundai Botswana has steadily grown from 200
cars a month in 1993 to 2,000 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
"From 1994, motor vehicle exports became Botwana's second
largest foregin exchange earner after diamonds," Minister of
Commerce and Industry George Kgoroba said.
</P>
<P>
"The plant has significantly contributed to the growth of our
economy and our policy of economic diversification."
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Botswana's total exports to South Africa were worth
351 million U.S. Dollars, of which motor vehicles accounted for
262 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year Botswana's total exports were up to 411 million U.S.
Dollars, and motor vehicles exports were 311 million U.S. Dollars
with 63 percent of motor exports being Hyundai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
