<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Banks Tighten Standards for Consumer Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Commercial banks in the U.S.
continue to tighten standards for consumer loans, a survey by the
U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) said today.
</P>
<P>
But the survey also showed that the pace of the tightening is
slowing down, suggesting that many banks believe they have
achieved sufficient protection against defaults.
</P>
<P>
The Fed's quarterly survey found that less than 25 percent of
the banks had tightened standards for credit card applications and
less than 10 percent had more stringent rules for other consumer
loans. Only 25 percent had lower borrowing limits on credit cards.
</P>
<P>
"The August survey was the seventh in a row that found a
tightening in standards for loans to households," the survey of
senior loan officers at 54 domestic and 21 foreign banks said.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that increased competition for business
credit apparently led many banks to ease terms on commercial and
industrial and commercial real estate loans.
</P>
<P>
The Fed added that a small but significant share of banks
reported easing standards on commercial real estate loans.
</P>
<P>
"Despite these tighter standards and terms, about 10 percent of
the banks, on net, said that their willingness to make consumer
installment loans had increased over the past three months," the
Fed said. It was the largest increase since the May 1995 survey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
