<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, August 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has
telephoned Jordan's King Hussein and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, asking them to persuade Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat to crack down on terrorism, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed on the phone Friday that the Palestinian
leader was not keeping his commitment to fight terrorism and this
was jeopardizing the entire peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's remarks coincided with a prevailing sense of
discontent in Israeli officials at Arafat's convening of
"national unity" conclaves with Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) and Islamic Jihad leaders early this week in Gaza and
Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The Burundi government said today it only wants
peace talks put off for two weeks or less after organizers
cancelled their Monday opening when asked for a postponement, a
report from the Burundi capital said.
</P>
<P>
Bujumbura is trying to contact international mediator and
former Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere to ask for a new date
for the talks, Institutional Reform Minister Eugene Nindorera was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I think it will be postponed for a small time only but Nyerere
might be very angry and he might take some severe decisions. We
are going to try to convince him that the delay is just for a few
days, two weeks probably, or less," he said.
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU -- Heavy fighting reportedly broke out between rival
factions in the western town of Baidoa Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Reports from field radios close to the town said at least one
hundred heavily armed militiamen from the Rahanwein Resistance
Army (RRA) attacked the town from the southern end and crushed the
main checkpoint, making their way through the center of the town,
245 km west of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the area said the RRA guerrilla fighters have
bitterly fought with the forces of Hussein Mohamed Aidid at a
place known as the presidential palace inside Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
Heavy looting also took place during the fighting which lasted
a few hours. The reports added that the RRA fighters were also
involved in ransacking several business stalls. Two communication
field radios (VHF) were also taken away by the RRA forces.
</P>
