<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan People Have Final Say on Tibet Issue: Official (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior Tibetan official in an
interview with Xinhua reporters today commented critical remarks
made by a US congressman who recently traveled to Tibet in the
guise of a tourist.
</P>
<P>
Raidi, chairman of the People's Congress of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, said Frank Wolf, a Republican congressman
from the state of Virginia, traveled to Tibet with ulterior
motives and spread irresponsible remarks intended to upset and
confuse the international community.
</P>
<P>
"All people with a sense of justice, including the Tibetan
people, are enraged by his actions," Raidi said.
</P>
<P>
Raidi spoke out after Wolf's secretive tour of Tibet, which he
followed up with a widely-covered new conference in the United
States on August 20.
</P>
<P>
"Who has the final say on the Tibetan issue?" Raidi
queried. "The Tibetan people, who have witnessed the profound
changes that have occurred in Tibet in the past four decades, are
the most qualified."
</P>
<P>
He said that Tibet before the democratic reform in 1959 was a
serf society which combined political and religious powers.
</P>
<P>
"Though only made up of the five percent of the Tibetan
population, the three categories of manorial lords, the former Tibet
local government, the monasteries and the nobility together ruled
Tibet and owned all the farmland, grassland and forests, as well
as the majority of livestock and production materials," Raidi
said. "The serfs, the overwhelming majority of the people, had no
political rights or personal freedom at all."
</P>
<P>
Tibet was liberated in 1951 and carried out a democratic reform
in 1959. "Under the leadership of the Communist Party of China,
Tibet experienced the most profound changes in its history during
the past 40 years, particularly after the democratic reform,"
Raidi said.
</P>
<P>
"The former serfs now are the masters of their own destiny. The
economy and culture have steadily developed and the living
standard of the people has kept improving," he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan People Have Final Say on Tibet Issue: Official (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to Wolf's remark that "China is swallowing Tibet,"
Raidi said that Wolf had lacked "the most basic common sense."
</P>
<P>
"Tibet has been an inseparable part of the Chinese territory
since after the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368)," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, the central government after 1959 has
motivated the whole country to support Tibet, which "registered
the fastest social-economic development in its history."
</P>
<P>
He quoted latest statistics to elaborate: The gross domestic
product in Tibet totaled 6.476 billion yuan in 1996, "posting
double-digit growth for successive years," he noted; the grain
output last year hit 775,000 tons, registering the ninth bumper
harvest in the past years; the foreign trade volume in 1996
reached more than 100 million US dollars; and the annual net
income of farmers and herdsmen hit 975 yuan.
</P>
<P>
"Now Tibet is witnessing a growing economy, stable political
situation, ethnic solidarity and improved living standards," he
said.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, in Lhasa, the regional capital, the city
proper has expanded from only three square kilometers in 1951 to
the current area of more than 50.
</P>
<P>
"Wolf said that he saw 'more Chinese in Lhasa than Tibetans.'
This can only reveal his ignorance or show his ulterior motives,"
Raidi said. "In fact, the Han nationals only account for three
percent of Tibet's total population," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that more Tibetans are now wearing
Western-style suits in public, finding such clothing more
practical and often necessary for their frequent exchanges with
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Even though the central government sent cadres and technicians
to Tibet for the purpose of advancing economic development, these
people return to the inland areas after their term of service,
according to Raidi.
</P>
<P>
"In this year alone, some 2,000 returned to their hometowns,"
he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
