<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Fighting Breaks out between Somali Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting reportedly
broke out between rival factions in the western town of Baidoa
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Reports from field radios close to the town said at least one
hundred heavily armed militiamen from the Rahanwein Resistance
Army (RRA) attacked the town from the southern end and crushed
the main checkpoint, making their way through the center of the
town, 245 km west of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the area said the RRA guerrilla fighters have
bitterly fought with the forces of Hussein Mohamed Aidid at a
place known as the presidential palace inside Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
Heavy looting also took place during the fighting which lasted
a few hours. The reports added that the RRA fighters were also
involved in ransacking several business stalls. Two
communication field radios (VHF) were also taken away by the RRA
forces.
</P>
<P>
There has been no clear picture about the casualty figures of
the fighting as all Baidoa radios were out of the air today.
However, the death of one person were confirmed, but the death
toll is believed to be much higher according to travellers
reaching Mogadishu today.
</P>
<P>
RRA spokesman Mohamud Ali Aden Qalinle in north Mogadishu told
the press that his forces have captured two technical battle
vehicles and a civilian car belonging to Hussein Aidid's men in
their operation last night.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle admitted that his forces have withdrawn from the town
early in the morning for what he described as a military tactic,
which he said was a complete success.
</P>
<P>
RRA have furthermore claimed to have released dozens of
prisoners from the central prison in the town.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle said his men who were involved in last night's attack
are currently stationed eight kilometers south of the town ready
to mount more attacks on target areas controlled by Hussein Aidid
in the region.
</P>
<P>
There's no word yet from Hussein Aidid's side over the
fighting in Baidoa which they controlled for nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
The RRA hit and run attacks in Bay and Bakol regions have been
increasing ever since the Ethiopian forces supported by the
militiamen from the Somali National Front faction invaded the
border region of Gedo.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopians are suspected to be equipping the RRA with
small arms, ammunition and other logistics in their campaign
against Hussein Aidid's faction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Arts Being Saved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Folk Arts Research
Institute has recovered and saved many Tibetan art forms in its
efforts to compile ten books covering folk songs, dance, music and
literature.
</P>
<P>
All the books will come before the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The 800,000-word "Collection of Tibetan Operas," published in
1996, provides information on the origins, schools and performance
troupes of all kinds of Tibetan operas.
</P>
<P>
Two collections will come out this year, one about folk dancing
and another on Quyi (Chinese folk art forms).
</P>
<P>
The institute, with the help of the central and regional
governments, has collected large quantities of material on Tibetan
folk arts, including 560-hours of tape recordings and about 600
hours of videotape, at least 8,000 pictures, and more than ten
million characters of written material, according to Tendzin
Cering, head of the institute.
</P>
<P>
He added that it is unusual, both at home and abroad, to
organize such a large-scale operation to save a local culture.
</P>
<P>
New art forms have been discovered during the survey, among
them is a dance called "Xian" from the Zhang-zhung Culture in the
northwest part of the region. Performances of this rare dance have
been highly praised by world experts.
</P>
<P>
The culture of monasteries, which are the dominant feature of
Tibetan life, has affected most art forms in the region, from
architecture and murals to music and dance. Some ancient religious
rites have also been resumed, like the devil's dance performed by
lamas at the Temple Zhaxi Lhunbo to exorcise evil spirits.
</P>
<P>
The central and regional governments have always attached great
importance to the preservation of folk arts, especially those of
the Tibetan ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
A special group consisting of department leaders from the
regional government was formed in 1986 to oversee the work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
