<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Visits Coast Where Killing Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 23 (Xinhua) - Kenyan President Daniel Arap Moi
today is touring Indian Ocean coastal region where bloodshed
violence entered the 11th day with death toll having hit an
estimated 45.
</P>
<P>
Two more people, who has sought refuge in Likoni Catholic
church in Mombasa, Kenya's second-largest city and key port, were
shot dead Friday morning by about 20 well-armed raiders with a
police officer seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
So far nobody knows where are the killers from, needless to
say their motives.
</P>
<P>
Moi, 73 and in power since 1978, last night flew into Mombasa,
under heavy security.
</P>
<P>
He said here Friday that the police are under instructions to
arrest anyone who incites violence, saying he was saddened by the
killings on the coast.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic violence erupted in the normally peaceful tourist
resort of Mombasa on August 13 and has spread to the northern and
southern coastal towns including Malindi, Kwale, Kilifi and Taita
Taveta.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, opposition leaders accused ruling Kenya
African National Union (KANU) of exploiting ethnic tensions and
dodging constitutional reforms ahead of multi-party elections
which Moi must call this year.
</P>
<P>
But Moi dismissed the allegations and said Friday the
constitution of the country is sacred and only through parliament
that the constitution could be repealed or revised.
</P>
<P>
He also announced he would not extend the term of parliament
as it is being demanded by the opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
A considerable amount of foreign tourists have reportedly
canceled their hotel booking in Mombasa and other tourist towns
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan police, strengthened by the General Service Unit
troops, have arrested hundreds of suspects, including two senior
activists with KANU and some supporters of the opposition in the
coastal area. 
</P>
