<HEADLINE> New Railway Project to be started in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Work on a long-awaited railway
line running through part of central Australia is expected to
start next year as the Australian federal government promised
today to provide a financial support for the 740 million U.S.
dollar project.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard pledged the support today
for Alice Springs-Darwin railway project, which was first planned
in 1911. The new railway will link the port city of Darwin in
northern Australia and Alice Springs in central Australia.
</P>
<P>
Together with the existing Alice Springs-Adelaide railway line,
the planned 1,410 km railway line will make it easier for the two
regions and neighboring areas to transport their mineral products
and farm products for export, particularly to Asia.
</P>
<P>
Darwin is Australia's nearest major port to Asia, Australia's
leading overseas market.
</P>
<P>
Work on the project is expected to begin in mid-1998 and to be
completed in 2002. 
</P>
