<HEADLINE> Adelaide Declaration on Aging passed by Professionals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Aged cared health professionals
today called on world leaders at a congress in Australia's
southern port city of Adelaide to immediately address issues
affecting the elderly, including abuse and neglect.
</P>
<P>
Delegates at the 1997 World Congress of Gerontology today
released the Adelaide Declaration on Aging entitled A Message for
World Leaders and Policy Makers.
</P>
<P>
"The findings reported at this congress have led us to a
profound concern for the quality of life of older people
everywhere," the declaration was quoted by the Australian
Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Poverty, malnutrition, disease, marginalization, abuse and
neglect were identified as major threats to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
The 16th World Congress was held in Adelaide from August 19-23
and attracted 1500 delegates from 60 countries.
</P>
<P>
The declaration called for wider education about ageing, more
research and improved policies and practices for aged care.
</P>
<P>
It advocated encouraging older people to have an active
lifestyle and looking after the elderly in their chosen
environment.
</P>
<P>
A report released during the conference found between 15
percent and 29 percent of frail older people living in Australian
nursing homes were physically restrained daily, the news agency
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
