<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Language Enriched by Scientific Terms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- With the development of modern
science and technology, more specialized terms are enriching the
old Tibetan language which is used by the Tibetan ethnic group
mainly inhabiting the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, known as the "roof of
the world."
</P>
<P>
At the time of its liberation in 1951, Tibet was a feudal serf
society which integrated politics and religion. Most of the
vocabulary of the Tibetan language was related to religion, daily
life, farming and recreational activities. There were few
scientific words.
</P>
<P>
"This indicates that the Tibetan ethnic group at that time was
little influenced by modern science and technology, for language
reflects the development of a society," said Hu Tan, a professor
with the China Tibetology Research Center, who participated in the
1997 Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies which ended today.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese-Tibetan Dictionary, published by the Nationalities
Publishing House in 1991, includes more than 80,000 entries
concerning modern science and technology. In recent years, words
in both Chinese and Tibetan languages, covering a number of
categories of natural sciences, have been newly-formed in the
Tibet Autonomous Region and its neighbor Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
"These words have greatly boosted economic growth and
scientific and technological progress in Tibet and other areas
inhabited by Tibetan people," said the professor who has been
studied the Tibetan language for more than four decades.
</P>
<P>
Hu explained that the terms are mainly created by academics, in
addition to some colloquialisms fashioned by the Tibetans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Language Enriched by Science Terms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For example, "clone" has been translated into "asexual
propagation," and the Tibetan expression for "computer" is
"electric brain or brain using electricity," which borrows its
usage from its Chinese equivalent.
</P>
<P>
Other terms adopt the method of transliteration.
</P>
<P>
"By now, the vocabulary in the Tibetan language about basic
sciences is complete, and the development of Tibetan has scored a
big step forward," Hu Tan said.
</P>
<P>
"However, considering the speed of scientific and technological
advancement in the world, the disparity remains rather large. The
Tibetan language has a long way to go to keep pace with the
times," he said.
</P>
<P>
In September 1995, a government-sponsored Tibetan language
standardization committee was formed to take charge of creating
science and technology terms in Tibetan, and also for
standardizing the words in current use.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, scientists and linguists in the Tibet
Autonomous Region and Qinghai, Gansu, Sichuan and Yunnan provinces
have been making concerted and persistent efforts to enrich the
Tibetan language.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the science terms appearing in Tibetan language
in recent years, the professor said, more new words have popped up
along with the reform, opening-up and modernization drive in
Tibet. The new words reflect the changes in various fields of
life, such as politics, economy, culture, education and sports.
</P>
<P>
At present, important government documents can be translated
into Tibetan language, and Tibetans who attend the annual sessions
of the National People's Congress (NPC) are able to receive
simultaneous interpretation, the professor said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Orchestra to Stage Symphony Concert in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese Oriental Bio
Philharmonic Orchestra (JOBPO) is to stage a concert here on
August 29 to mark the 25th Anniversary of the normalization of
relations between China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
