<HEADLINE> New Railway Project to be started in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Work on a long-awaited railway
line running through part of central Australia is expected to
start next year as the Australian federal government promised
today 74 million U.S. dollars financial support for the 740
million U.S. dollars project.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard pledged the support today
for Alice Springs-Darwin railway project, which was first planned
in 1911.
</P>
<P>
The planned 1,410 km railway line, which will link the port
city of Darwin in northern Australia and Alice Springs in central
Australia, would provide direct economic benefits to the two
states of the Northern Territory and the South Australia, or the
central part of continental Australian.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the rail link provide an important
psychological boost to central region.
</P>
<P>
The planned railway line, together with the existing Alice
Springs-Adelaide railway line, will make it easier for the two
regions and neighboring areas to transport their mineral products
and farm products for export, particularly to Asia.
</P>
<P>
Darwin is Australia's nearest major port to Asia, Australia's
leading overseas market.
</P>
<P>
Work on the project is expected to begin in mid-1998, with the
project to be completed in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The federal government contribution, which fell short of the
220 million U.S. dollars requested by the two regions, will be
added to the 74 million U.S. dollars pledged by the two regions,
with the remaining 518 million U.S. dollars to be funded by the
private sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
