<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 23 (Xinhua) --Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has telephoned Jordan's King Hussein and
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, asking them to persuade
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to crack down on terrorism,
Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed on the phone Friday that the Palestinian
leader was not keeping his commitment to fight terrorism and
this was jeopardizing the entire peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's remarks coincided with a prevailing sense of
discontent in Israeli officials at Arafat's convening of
"national unity" conclaves with Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) and Islamic Jihad leaders early this week in Gaza and
Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Arafat's show of cordiality toward Hamas and
Islamic Jihad leaders, Israeli Cabinet secretary Dan Naveh
Thursday assailed Arafat for initiating the "national unity"
talks, saying he is "two-faced."
</P>
<P>
"If he is truly a partner in peace, the way he claims he is,
he must fight these organizations and certainly not embrace
them," Naveh said.
</P>
<P>
But Palestinian officials contended that the dialogue between
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and the Islamic
fundamentalists was not being held to appease Hamas but to assert
Palestine Liberation Organization's (PLO) domination.
</P>
<P>
"I can not understand what Netanyahu is worried about. We are a
society which believes in democracy and pluralism. We will not
allow Hamas to form an alternative society," chief Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat stressed.
</P>
<P>
Erekat alleged that "Netanyahu has brought relations between
the Israeli and Palestinian people to their worst point since
the beginning of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Nabil Abu Rudeness, chief adviser to Arafat, also said that
the PLO was leading the meeting and that "our strategic choice
is peace."
</P>
<P>
He explained Arafat's "all options are open" remark at the
opening session of the "national unity" Wednesday as meaning that
"if Israel is not interested in peace it will push Palestinians
to reconsider things." 
</P>
