<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Wants Peace Talks Put Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Burundi government said
today it only wants peace talks put off for two weeks or less
after organizers cancelled their Monday opening when asked for a
postponement, a report from the Burundi capital said today.
</P>
<P>
Bujumbura is trying to contact international mediator and
former Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere to ask for a new date
for the talks, Institutional Reform Minister Eugene Nindorera was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"i think it will be postponed for a small time only but
Nyerere might be very angry and he might take some severe
decisions. We are going to try to convince him that the delay is
just for a few days, two weeks probably, or less," he said.
</P>
<P>
Burundi Officials said the government would also consult with
Nyerere's envoy to Bujumbura Felix Mosha, who arrived in Burundi
on Thursday and is expected to leave later today.
</P>
<P>
An aide of Nyerere's said Friday the talks, which had been
scheduled to start in Arusha, a northern tanzanian town Monday,
were cancelled because Bujumbura had asked for a delay.
</P>
<P>
However, organizers in Tanzania said today Burundi peace talks
would still open Monday but without the Burundi government team
since it asked for a delay.
</P>
<P>
He said the talks would start as originally scheduled Monday
in the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Bujumbura requested a postponement on the grounds that
successful talks were unlikely. U.N. Security Council members
Thursday pressed Burundi and Tanzania to improve relations ahead
of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Nindorera said today that Tanzania remains a viable talks
venue although the Burundi government accuses Tanzania of
harboring Burundi a Hutu rebels on its western border.
</P>
<P>
He said Nyerere's envoy Mosha came to Burundi and only told
the government how the talks were to be organized.
</P>
<P>
"We need more time to prepare so the negotiations can be
useful," he said.
</P>
<P>
The military government, formed after a coup by the
Tutsi-dominated army in July last year, also accuses Tanzania of
being behind a decision last weekend to maintain regional
sanctions against Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The talks would have brought together the Burundi government
and the main Hutu rebel group the National Council for the
Defemse of Democracy (CNDD) for the first time in a public
forum.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the pro-Tutsi Uprona party, the
Hutu-dominated Frodebu party and parliament were to have joined
the talks aimed at ending Burundi's civil war and political
crisis in the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
