<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Abacha Gears up for ECOWAS Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Repeated clashes have been reported between ECOMOG troops and
soldiers of the junta, but neither side has seemingly gained
substantial achievements.
</P>
<P>
No one could imagine ECOMOG troops would leave Sierra Leone
with internationally-condemned coupists still holding the power,
not to mention the oath of ECOWAS to restore civil rule there.
</P>
<P>
This, according to analysts, determines that the key objective
of Abacha's visits would focus on persuading his hosts to stand
by him.
</P>
<P>
So far, no response of the countries Abacha visited has been
released. But he is reported to be in the view that if the
military junta failed to explore the avenue to bow out honorably,
it might eventually be sent packing by force, as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
Then there comes a problem how the junta is given the chance
to show its willingness to step down "honorably" since its demand
to participate in the summit has been rejected and peace talks
which collapsed last month has not be resumed.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah will
represent Sierra Leone at the summit in Abuja next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
While observers are expecting a breakthrough in the political
impasse caused by the junta's belligerent position, the United
Nations Security Council has expressed its support to any actions
ECOWAS might adopt to settle the crisis in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The council President John Weston said earlier this week the
key objective of the 15-member body now was to ensure that it was
speaking and acting with the same voice as ECOWAS ministers
regarding the Sierra Leonean issue.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has issued three statements urging the junta to
reinstate the elected government without delay. So has the
Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
All this might be a great encouragement to General Abacha in
his capacity as both ECOWAS chairman and military ruler of west
Africa's "big brother".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, as the one-year chairmanship is shared by ECOWAS
members on a rotation basis, Abacha's recent high-frequency
foreign visits may not be unconnected with an attempt to seek a
second term.
</P>
<P>
Without the capacity of ECOWAS chairmanship, it will be
difficult for Nigeria to play its leading role in the sub-region,
observers here said.
</P>
<P>
Then it will equally be an arduous task to maintain peace and
stability in west Africa as far as the tense situation in Sierra
Leone is concerned, without Nigeria's positive contribution in
terms of both human and materials resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
