<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abu Simbel to Have Sound and Light Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- International bids for sound and
light plays will be submitted before the end of this year in Abu
Simbel, Egypt's famous archeological site that hosts four ancient
colossal stone statues in the wildness of sand.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Company for Sound and Light has finalized contracts
with a number of foreign companies to implement the sound and
light project, the Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The whole project is planned to be completed in eight months,
said Yousri Mohamed Hassan, director of the Aswan-based sound and
light company.
</P>
<P>
The company has sent a delegation to Abu Simbel to do research
on the various dimensions of the project and the impact of the
light on monuments, he said.
</P>
<P>
The project is part of an Egyptian campaign to promote tourism
development in the southern part of the country and increase the
number of tourist nights.
</P>
<P>
Abu Simbel, a key tourist site in Aswan about 900 kilometers
south of Cairo, is a rock-hewn temple carved into a jutting
promontory in the land of Nubia.
</P>
<P>
Twice a year, at the dawning of the spring and autumnal
equinoxes, the first beams of the rising sun shed flush on the
faces of four-seated figures (three gods and Ramsis II, Egypt's
longest-ruling pharaoh, whose reign was between 1304 to 1237 BC).
</P>
<P>
The sound and light show, a colorful entertainment combining a
pharaoh's autobiographical account and mock scenes in ancient
times, has been staged at Egypt's hallmarks -- three pyramids of
Giza and Sphinx. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
