<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Parole Dodgers Vanish in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- More than 5,000 convicts
are on the run after skipping parole and absconding from
correctional supervision in Johannesburg and Pretoria region, and
no one is actively searching for them.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, almost 4,000 hardened criminals have made a dash
for freedom while on parole after serving sentences, a local
weekly magazine Saturday Star reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, over 1,400 people who were sentenced
to correctional supervision, a more lenient punishment which is
served at home and subject to regular visits by prison officials,
have also slipped out of the hands of the law.
</P>
<P>
These convicts have leaked out of the criminal justice system
since 1992, and most of them are on wanted lists at police
stations across South Africa, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, the report further claimed, only a handful of
escaped convicts are re-arrested.
</P>
<P>
The over-burdened South African police service already has its
handful trying to trace people who have escaped from police
custody before conviction.
</P>
<P>
The police released alarming statistics this week, showing
there were more than 700 breakouts from police cells around the
country in the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 crime suspects escaped from police custody
during these breakouts.
</P>
<P>
National Police Commissioner Georgy Fivaz this week warned
station commissioners that they would have to take responsibility
for escapes at their stations.
</P>
<P>
The station chiefs would face severe disciplinary action for
staff negligence that led to cell breakouts, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
