<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow River Flows Again in Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Water flowed from the upper
reaches of the Yellow River yesterday for the first time in more
than six months, to the mouth of the river in east China's
Shandong Province, where there was a serious shortage of water.
</P>
<P>
Since February 7, the upper reaches of the Yellow River, which
runs though most of north China, have been dry, and the lower part
of the river had no water for 147 days, the longest period on
record in this century.
</P>
<P>
The city of Dongying and the Binzhou region near the river
mouth have suffered from a serious drought since this spring, and
the area had difficulty obtaining the large amounts of river water
needed for irrigation, industry and everyday use.
</P>
<P>
The State Council and National Water-Control Headquarters paid
close attention to the water shortage and drought in the
area. Meanwhile, the Yellow River Water-Control Committee exerted
considerable effort to bring the water down from the upper reaches
to lower reaches and river mouth area, by taking measures to limit
the use of water in the areas along the upper reaches of the
river.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
