<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Committed to Implementing Tight Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- China's largest economic and
financial center, Shanghai, will continue to practice a moderately
tight monetary policy in the remaining months of this year to
support economic growth and state enterprise reform, a senior
banking official said.
</P>
<P>
The moderately tight monetary policy is aimed to cut bad loans,
control the money supply, improve financial services and prevent
financial risks, said Mao Yingliang, president of the Shanghai
branch of the People's Bank of China, the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Mao said that the proportion of non-performing loans should be
reduced by two percentage points in a bid to improve credit
quality.
</P>
<P>
Efforts should be made to strengthen the management of cash and
strictly control the money supply, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is an arduous task for us to control the supply of money,"
Mao said, urging all local banks to make greater efforts to
withdraw money from circulation.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that financial services will be improved to
render greater support to the reform and development of the
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Banks should take an active part in the work involved in
enterprise mergers and bankruptcy, Mao added.
</P>
<P>
He noted, however, that commercial banks are prohibited from
extending bank credits into the stock market and must not accept
deposits or grant loans illegally.
</P>
<P>
Both financial opening and refrom will be deepened in the
remaining months, Mao said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
