<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ashrawi Warns Against Israel's Anti-Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- In another sign indicating
further worsening of relations between the right-wing Israeli
government and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), a senior
Palestinian official has warned Israel not to kill the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Hanan Ashrawi, minister of Higher Education and former
spokeswoman for the Palestinian peace delegation, said today that
the PNA is taking seriously a report that Israel is forming
special units to carry out assassinations and other operations in
the Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi issued the warning when she was speaking to reporters
in the West Bank city of Ramallah following a late night meeting
of the Palestinian leadership composed of cabinet members, PLO
executive members and speakers of the Palestinian National Council
and Palestinian Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
On Friday Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu phoned President
Mubarak of Egypt and King Hussein of Jordan, asking them to use
their influence on Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to change
what he called a policy toward terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu claimed that Arafat was not keeping his commitment
to fighting terrorism and was jeopardizing the entire peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security sources were quoted as saying in Israel Radio
saying Friday that the PNA was refusing to arrest some 200 Hamas
activists, who, Israel believes, might be linked to the last
month's Jerusalem suicide bombing attack killing 14 Israelis and
wounding dozens more.
</P>
<P>
The sources also expressed disappointment with the fruitless
meeting in Ramalla Thursday night attended by Israeli, Palestinian
and U.S. security officials, which focused on investigation into
the suicide bombing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to a report of the U.S. TV network, CNN,
the Israeli authorities have launched a campaign to marginalize
Arafat since the peace process hit the rock bottom.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Ilan, Netanyahu's senior advisor, told CNN that
Arafat has used terrorism as "a weapon in trying to achieve
what he wants to achieve." "This is one weapon which is used
simultaneously with another weapon which is negotiations," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
