<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao's Portuguese Civil Servants Leaving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 1,000 Macao civil servants
coming from Portugal will be leaving by the end of next year, a
civil service official said.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Baptista Bruxo, director of the Public Administration and
Function Service Department, told the local newspaper "Tai Chung
Pou" that those people will leave before 1999 after their
contracts expire.
</P>
<P>
Macao now has some 990 contracted Portuguese civil
servants. Most of them will not get renewal of their contract term
and will have to return to Portugal next year, the director said.
</P>
<P>
The localization of civil service is deemed one of the leading
tasks in the transitional period of Macao. Up until now, most the
middle and senior positions are held by those from Portugal.
</P>
<P>
The total forces of Macao civil servants have gradually
expanded to more than 18,000, compared with a total population of
some 420,000.
</P>
<P>
The director said that their leaving will not affect the normal
function of government departments, as most departments would have
been well prepared by the time of their leaving.
</P>
<P>
However, Bruxo said that before December 31, 1998, government
departments can still submit applications to the governor to hire
some individual Portuguese civil servants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Abacha Gears up for ECOWAS Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state General
Sani Abacha, who used to spends almost all his time to manage the
country in the state house in the capital Abuja, has launched a
whirlwind of foreign trips this week.
</P>
<P>
He ended a one-day official visit to Mali and the Gambia on
Friday, following a similar one to Cote d'Ivoire and Guinea on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
As Chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), General Abacha also visited Ghana and Benin in late
July.
</P>
<P>
All these countries covered by his rare foreign visits are
members of the sub-regional organization that is to hold its 20th
summit of heads of state and government next week.
</P>
<P>
There must be quite a few issues there for the leaders to
discuss with each other, particularly on how to keep the
16-member body on the right track to its ultimate goal of
economic integration and a common market in west Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, no economic achievement can be made without a
peaceful and stable environment when collective efforts are
emphasized to bring common prosperity to the sub-region, which is
believed to be a club with the biggest number of the world's
poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
The view of peace and stability ahead of development was
shared among west African leaders when they met at a summit last
year.
</P>
<P>
It is therefore logic that General Abacha's recent diplomatic
initiatives dwell on the crisis in Sierra Leone, which has posed
a threat to regional peace and stability, especially after the
return of normalcy in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
West African countries stood up to call for an immediate
return of power to Sierra Leone's legitimate government shortly
after it was overthrown by a military coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS, which also embraces Sierra Leone, set up a committee
composed of Nigeria, Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire and Guinea to tackle
the crisis in a combination of three measures -- dialogue,
sanctions and the use of force.
</P>
<P>
To date, dialogue has been failed as the military junta
insists on staying in power until the year 2001, while tightened
sanctions and embargo seem not to put enough pressure on the
coupists.
</P>
<P>
The last option, namely military intervention, has now been
placed before ECOWAS members to decide.
</P>
<P>
However, it is obviously a difficult decision to make,
especially when Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire and Guinea are reported not
to share the same zeal with Nigeria in resolving the Sierra
Leonean crisis by force.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian troops are already in the troubled country under a
defense pact with the ousted civilian government and reportedly
supported by their comrades-in-arms from a few west African
countries in the name of west African peace-keeping force known
as ECOMOG. (to be continued)





