<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Children Spending Billions of Marks Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Annual spending by German children
and youth runs as high as 15 to 20 billion marks (8 to 11 billion
U.S. dollars), which is equal to about three percent of the annual
retail sales of the country, a German retailers' group said today.
</P>
<P>
This consumption group spends most of its money on music,
sports and fashion. Music and sports idols like "Backstreet Boys"
and Michael Jordan have an extremely strong influence on
children's spending behavior, said Thomas Werz, leader of the
German Retailers Association.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more and more of this youth group's money is flowing
into computer markets, Werz said, adding that computers in
children's rooms alone are worth 5 billion marks (2.7 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to his estimates, more than half of all German
children between the ages of six and nine now have their own
computers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
