<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Foreign Minister Leaves on 6-Nation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today expressed hope that his multi-leg tour of southern
Africa could achieve good results in economic cooperation field.
</P>
<P>
He was making the remarks in an interview to Good Morning Egypt
on local TV station before embarking on the trip early this
morning to six African states of Lesotho, South Africa,
Mozambique, Zambia, Malawi and Botswana.
</P>
<P>
He said he will deliver messages from President Hosni Mubarak
to the African leaders on bilateral relations, political matters
on common interests and means of boosting economic ties.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said his talks with African officials will cover
investments, trade, tourism and economic cooperation and several
agreements will be signed in this score.
</P>
<P>
The African tour, the second of the kind by Moussa this year,
is regarded as another show of Egypt's interest in promoting
economic and political links within the continent. He is being
accompanied by a large team of businessmen and representatives of
private sector companies.
</P>
<P>
"This tour will cover political matters at both the African and
Mideast levels. But mainly it will focus on consolidating economic
ties," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian foreign minister said a similar tour to East
Africa last May, during which he visited Kenya, Zimbabwe, Uganda
and Nigeria, is "very fruitful."
</P>
<P>
During Moussa's two-day visit to Pretoria, South Africa, his
second leg of his tour, the two countries will sign five
agreements covering cooperation in taxation, marine and air
transport, culture and technology.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will also sign a number of accords on trade and
investment with Mozambique, according to today's Egyptian Mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
