<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adjusts Development Goals for Chemical Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- China's top chemical official
says the country has adjusted the chemical industry's development
goals to keep up with the fast growth of the sector in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Gu Xulian, Chinese minister of Chemical Industry, recently told
Xinhua that her ministry has revised the industry target to earn
20 billion US dollars from chemical exports in the year 2000,
double the figure set in the previous plan.
</P>
<P>
The aggregate overseas investment used by the country's
chemical sector till the year 2000 is to increase from the current
six billion dollars to 12 billion dollars, or 20 percent more than
the target set six years ago, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The foreign trade volume of China's chemical industry in 2000
is proposed to reach 40 billion dollars, she said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the ministry plans to foster 100 enterprises and
enterprise groups that are well-equipped, well-managed and
competitive in the international market, she added.
</P>
<P>
The chemical industry, recognized one of the basic industries
and one of the key sectors in the former development plan for
China's economy, is also used by the Chinese government to attract
overseas capital and boost export-oriented economy.
</P>
<P>
To this end, China is to expand the channels for raising
capital and present more flexible means of development for
overseas investors, according to Gu.
</P>
<P>
Her ministry has planned to increase the use of export credits
and other commercial loans while concentrating efforts on "drawing
investments from major multinationals and putting it into key
projects as well as major technical renovation projects."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, she said that the ministry has decided to offer more
incentives for those who are involved in regional chemical
development and encourage overseas investors to package smaller
projects into bigger ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adjusts Development Goals for Chemical Industry (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the existing cooperative projects, overseas investors will
be encouraged to broaden their business scope to such new fields
as upgraded chemicals and chemicals for the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
Eventually, the ministry expects to foster a group of new
exported-oriented chemical industrial bases in the country with
the aid of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
Gu said the introduction and application of new- and high-tech
chemical techniques should also be put on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the ministry, China's chemical
industry in the past five years registered its fastest growth ever.
</P>
<P>
The total foreign trade volume between 1992 and 1996 came to
110.4 billion US dollars, of which export amounted to 46.1 billion
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The industry posted a total export volume of 12 billion dollars
and a trade volume of 30 billion dollars in 1996, up 230 percent
and 190 percent over that of 1992.
</P>
<P>
The accumulated overseas investment utilized by the chemical
sector in the past five years hit six billion dollars. The
investment of some 150 projects exceeded 10 million dollars each,
and there are 6,800 chemical ventures with overseas investment
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ministry expanded its cooperation with foreign
governments and corporations. Of the 25 leading chemical
multinationals, 70 percent have set up operations in China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Ministry of Chemical Industry has signed all-round
cooperative agreements with eight foreign government departments,
including those from the Netherlands, Mexico, the United States
and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, similar relations were established between the
ministry and 13 other corporations such as America's DuPont,
Germany's Holst and Bayer, Britain's Imperial Chemical
Incorporation and Rhone-Poulenc of France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
