<HEADLINE> Chinese Government's Tibet Policy Is Good: Western Scholars (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- A number of Western scholars
said that the Chinese government's policy toward Tibet is a good
one, when they addressed the Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies,
which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Po You Hsing, from the US, said that Tibet has entered a
new era since the mid-20th century, putting an end to its feudal
system of serfdom.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government has allocated a lot of money and sent
many personnel to help improve Tibetan economy...the facts are
known to the whole world," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Tibet was officially incorporated into the
Chinese territory in the 13th century. "The Tibetan people are
members of the Chinese family, and the region is an inseparable
part of China," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that a few people who advocate the independence of
Tibet have even colluded with those who blow the trumpet of Taiwan
independence. People who support the unification of the motherland
are not happy to see what these groups are doing, he added.
</P>
<P>
Colin Mackerras, president of Griffith University in Australia,
told Xinhua that the Chinese government's policy toward Tibet is a
wise one because it encourages the survival of the Tibetan
culture. And the modernization drive in Tibet is also positive, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Religion, architecture and Tibetan arts will always remain,"
he said, adding: "There will be more blending of cultures. But I
don't think that the distinctive Tibetan culture is going to be
lost or disappear."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that many people in the West have said that the
Chinese government is destroying Tibetan culture, but that does
not correspond with what he has seen.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think it is a wise way to maintain Tibetan culture by
splitting Tibet from China. If it is split from China, it would be
very bad economically, and also would be very dangerous," he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government's Tibet Policy Is Good: Western Scholars (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nancy Levine, a professor from the University of California,
said that a policy which takes local conditions into consideration
is being adopted in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
She noted that modernization is reshaping Tibetan people's way
of life. There is no need for people to work 30 days a month
nowadays, residents have more time to travel.
</P>
<P>
"They are good things," she said.
</P>
<P>
Elaine Roboson, a British scholar who has visited Tibet four
times, said she saw for herself that the Tibetan people are
enjoying high religious freedom, and can follow any religious
belief they choose.
</P>
<P>
Graham Clarke, a British professor studying Tibetan economy,
said that the region is undergoing rapid economic change, and,
locally, economic development is welcomed.
</P>
<P>
Lawrence Epstein, a professor from the University of
Washington, said that since the 1980s, the Tibetan people have
been exploiting ethnic and natural resources, including developing
tourism, and the local ways of life have been largely reshaped. At
the same time, the process has enhanced the locals' self-awareness
of the Tibetan culture.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting, sponsored by the Tibetan Studies Center
and the third of its kind in China, touched on issues of
socio-economics, religion, culture and language in Tibet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
