<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM to Visit France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri will pay an official visit to France next month, indicating
that the good bilateral relations will not be affected by the
recent French elections.
</P>
<P>
The recent French elections, which ousted Lebanon's traditional
right-wing allies from power, aroused fears in Lebanon that
Lebanese relations with France will be affected, local Daily Star
newspaper said in comment of the visit today.
</P>
<P>
Political sources said last night that Hariri will start his
three-day trip on September 11 and will be accompanied by key
members of the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Hariri was formally invited by his French counterpart and
socialist leader, Lionel Jospin, who assumed office in June after
defeating the right-wing supporters of President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
There had been speculation that Lebanon would fall victim to
the tense relations between Chirac, Hariri's personal friend and
ally, and Jospin.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that topping the agenda of the political
discussion is the Middle East situation and south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine
plans to visit Beirut as part of a Middle East tour that
aims to emphasize the new government's commitment to a role in
the region's peace-making effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
