<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Healthier Children in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Books on how to bring up better
children are popular in east China's Shanghai, and statistics show
that there were 2.4 million children below the age of 14 by the
end of 1996, accounting for 18 percent of the city's population.
</P>
<P>
There are medical centers all over the city for pregnant women
and infants, and more than 85 percent of the children have been
vaccinated. The city's infant mortality rate and incidence of
physical defects has dropped to the level of developed countries.
</P>
<P>
It is common for parents to attend special classes on how to
raise children scientifically.
</P>
<P>
Children between the ages of three and six get preschool
education, where they learn to count, draw, and sing.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 2,470 kindergartens in the city, with
268,200 children.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has nine years of compulsory education that is
tuition-free. Local governments at different levels spent a total
of 5.8 billion yuan (728 million US dollars) on education last
year, 4.6 times the amount six years ago.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, about 99.9 percent of school-age children were in
school, and 98.3 percent of the pupils graduated from primary
schools.
</P>
<P>
The city also established a "child protection and education
center", which has taken in more than 100 children with family
troubles. The center not only provides them with psychological
help but also finds ways to help them reunite with their parents.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there are 39 special schools helping educate more
than 6,000 mentally retarted children. The city also has 21
centers for deaf children, which have helped 148 children receive
treatment and go to ordinary kindergartens and schools.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
