<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loans Helping Education in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Elementary education in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has been greatly improved
through the help of loans provided by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The region's largest overseas-funded education project for
improving education conditions in poverty-stricken areas, is
scheduled for completion in 1999. The project will cost an
estimated 360 million yuan (about 45 million US dollars),
including 19.3 million US dollars in loans provided by the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen of the region's most impoverished counties will
benefit greatly from the project, which will help build school
buildings and libraries, supply better facilities, and train
better teachers for local schools. So far, these counties have
built 270,000 sq.m. of school buildings, bought 40,000 desks and
chairs, and trained more than 6,800 teachers and staff members.
</P>
<P>
Elementary education in Xinjiang has remained at a low level as
a result of a shortage of education funds and facilities. The
region is inhabited by many ethnic groups and textbooks have to be
written in different languages, adding further to complications in
elementary education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
