<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Government Announces End of Food Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian government has taken
measures to ensure that this traditional agricultural country will
have enough to feed its people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters recently, Prime Minister Ivan Kostov, and
Minister of Agriculture Ventsislav Varbanov reassured that the
grain crisis earlier this year would not recur, and the bread
price will remain stable.
</P>
<P>
Their reassurance was based on an optimistic assessment of this
year's wheat harvest, and the government's compulsive wheat
purchasing policies.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, Bulgaria enjoyed an average of one third of grain
production surplus each year. But since early 1990s, the country
has been suffering from a dramatic drop in production, due to
economic problems facing the country.
</P>
<P>
The grain shortage culminated in a serious food crisis in
February this year when the country had to purchase 280,000 tons
of wheat from Poland. Enitem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
