<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Take Lion's Share in Finswimming Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Russian swimmers bagged
home four out of six gold medals at stake on Friday at the 4th
Youth World Finswimming Championships in Balatonfuzfo, Hungary.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 50 meters finals, Uljanov Ilja of Russia clocked
his winning time of 16.21, beating Chinese Li Jing to second and
Italian Solieri Mirko the third.
</P>
<P>
The men's 400 meters crown went to Russian Ivanov Pavel who
touched home first in 3:16.18. Chinese Gao Shang won the silver
with the bronze medal taken by Greek Bazos Dimitrios.
</P>
<P>
The Russian men's quartet also took the title in the 4x200
meters in 6:16.36, beating their Chinese peers to second and the
Czech Republic third.
</P>
<P>
The fourth gold for Russia was awarded by Komarova Tatiana in
the women's 100 meters in 40.93 seconds, with a Chinese duo of Yin
Jun and Chen Cuiheng finished second and third respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, Chen Cuiheng also choked up her gold medal in the 200
meters by clocking in 1:40.23. Russian Koroleva Oksana took the
silver and Frenchwoman Louison Lea won the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
The other gold medal was taken by Uspenska Julia of Ukraine in
the women's 800 meters wherein she finished first in 7:33.69,
beating Russians Kachmina Ekaterina and Koroleva Oksana to second
and third.
</P>
<P>
In the past three-day competitions, China had notched up five
golds, seven silvers and four bronzes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
