<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 70 Rebels killed in Friday's Fighting in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- About 70 Tamil rebels were
killed and many others injured Friday when government troops
continued their attack on the rebel-control Puliyankulam town in
the Northern province of Sri Lanka, a military spokesman here
said today.
</P>
<P>
Ink Dewage, the spokesman, said the troops, advancing north
westwards from the Puliyankulam railway station Friday, had
retaliated with tank fire and artillery to force the rebels to
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
Progress on Friday was slow due to the fact that the rebels
fired mortars and automatic weapons from well prepared defenses,
he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said one officer and six soldiers were killed in the
fighting on Friday. Four officers and 29 soldiers were also
wounded.
</P>
<P>
However, Dewage noted that very satisfactory results are being
achieved since troops have been able to draw and kill large groups
of rebels in their concentrations.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan troops launched operation "Jaya Sikuru" (Sure of
Victory) in May to capture the 90-km highway that links Vavuniya
to Kilinochchi further north.
</P>
<P>
This was the third day the government troops continued their
attack on Puliyankulam, a town near a vital supply route that runs
from Colombo to the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting a guerrilla war for a
separate state in the north and east of the island country since
1983.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
