<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Financial Secretary Leaves on Visit to Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Donald Tsang, financial
secretary of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region's (SAR)
government, left here today on a week-long visit to Australia,
expected to be focused on bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Tsang told reporters at the press room of
the SAR government that he will also brief the Australians on his
"experience over the last two months working in the Hong Kong SAR
government" and will update them "on the economic performance in
Hong Kong" and his "idea of economic prospect in the years to
come."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that his trip would promote bilateral
economic cooperation and, particularly, Australia's investment in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Questioned about the recent rise-and-fall waves at Hong Kong's
stock market, Tsang said: "The so-called crisis is more or less
over," and "I am pretty confident that we are able to cope with
whatever problems that may come our way as far as currency is
concerned."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Hong Kong has a well-established system of
dealing with attacks on currency of one or another.
</P>
<P>
During his current visit to Australia, Tsang will visit Sydney,
Canberra and Melbourne where he will call on political and
business leaders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
