Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Since fighting broke out between forces loyal to Prince
Norodom Ranariddh and those of Hun Sen, from 25,000 to 35,000
Cambodians have taken refuge in the Kap Choeng refugee camp hastily
built by Thailand seven kilometers from the Camdodian border not far
from Anlong Veng, the last stronghold of the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
-- Sixty-three men, women and children were massacred in Algeria
from Wednesday night to Thursday morning in the village of Souhane
southeast of Algiers, according witnesses living in the village. A
dozen girls were abducted by the killers, who were assumed to be
members of the Armed Islamic Group, who have killed about 900
civilians after the legislative election held on June 5.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The stock markets in Europe lived another difficult day on
Friday with all the indexes in Frankfurt, Amsterdam, Zurich, London
and Paris falling. The operators are expecting a rise of interest
rates by the German Bundesbank, which is worried about the tension
caused by inflation in Germany.
</P>
<P>
-- General Pero Colic, chief of staff of the Bosnian Serb army,
Friday abruptly broke his reserve over the power struggle in
Republika Srpska (RS) by publicly disavowing President Biljana
Plavsic, accusing her of trying to ``undermine the state'' of RS.
</P>
