<HEADLINE> Western Scholars Criticize Wolf's Remarks as "Absolutely nonsense"(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Religion, architecture and Tibetan arts will always remain,"
he said, adding: "There will be more blending of cultures. But I
don't think that the distinctive Tibetan culture is going to be
lost or disappear."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that many people in the West have said that the
Chinese government is destroying Tibetan culture, but that does
not correspond with what he has seen in the region.
</P>
<P>
"I sincerely believe that the Chinese government is extending
every possible effort to preserve Tibetan culture," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mackerras added that Tibetan traditions are stronger in the
1990s and are, in fact, stronger than virtually any other
traditional culture in China.
</P>
<P>
He voiced total disagreement with those who advocate the need
to split Tibet from China to maintain the region's distinctive
traditions.
</P>
<P>
"It would be economically unsound and dangerous to split Tibet
from China," said Mackerras, "and it would devastate the local
cultural tradition."
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government's policy toward Tibet is a wise one
because it encourages the survival of the Tibetan culture. And the
modernization drive in Tibet is also positive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Elaine Robson, a British scholar who has visited Tibet four
times, said she saw for herself that the Tibetan people are
enjoying high religious freedom, and can follow any religious
belief they choose.
</P>
<P>
Graham Clarke, a British professor studying Tibetan economy,
said that the region is undergoing rapid economic change, and,
locally, economic development is welcomed.
</P>
</TEXT>
