<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The World Bank has approved a 30-million-U.S. dollar
loan to Jordan to help people find jobs and build roads and
schools.
</P>
<P>
A Bank source said that the loan for an infrastructure project
in Jordan would create temporary jobs and help "improve the living
and safety conditions of some 1.5 million people in urban squatter
settlements and refugee camps, and in rural settlements,"
semi-official Jordan Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The infrastructure project is a component of the government's
social productivity program and will be used as a model for
similar infrastructure program in the future.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Britain-based Rolls-Royce company and its two
Jordanian partners have formed a joint venture in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Reyrolle, Rolls-Royce's electricity transmission and
distribution branch, on Thursday formally linked with the
Jordanian Electricity Utilities and transformer manufacturer
Electrical Equipment Industries Co. Ltd. (ELICO) to establish the
new company, Jordan Electrical Switchgear Co. (JESCO),
semi-official Jordan Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
JESCO will initially produce and sell Reyrolle's Guardian
range of medium voltage switchgear.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture will start production in 1998 in a new
factory in Amman.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- An interline agreement has been signed between
Mongolia's national airline, MIAT, and Israel's national carrier,
EL AL, following two years of negotiations, reported bi-weekly
Israel Business Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, MIAT offers travelers flights to Mongolia
via Berlin, Moscow and Istanbul, as well as to Seoul, Osaka,
Beijing, Alma Mata and a number of other destinations in Russia
and China.
</P>
<P>
Fabian Sewirski, general manager of MIAT's Israeli
representative, GSA, said that a consular treaty had been
recently signed between Israel and Mongolia which exempts citizens
of both countries from the need to obtain a tourist visa.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli finance ministry plans to begin
raising 450 million U.S. dollars from the public this month
through the issue of Government Bonds, reported bi-weekly Israel
Business Friday.
</P>
<P>
The program calls for the issue of 250 million dollar worth of
index-linked Saggi and Galil-category bonds and a further 200
million dollars of unlinked Kfir and Shahar-class bonds.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israel National Science Foundation (NSF) has
decided to allocate a total of 30 million U.S. dollars this year
to fund research programs, reported bi-weekly Israel Business
Friday.
</P>
<P>
This represents a rise of 25 percent compared with the amount
of financial research aid awarded in 1996. Nearly half of the
supported funds are in the fields of the exact sciences and
technologies, with much of the remainder pertaining to life
sciences and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The NSF is the country's major funding body for competitive
scientific research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
