<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, August 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- The official daily newspaper Minju Choson in the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Saturday carried a
commentary, criticizing the remarks by some Japanese government
officials that violate China's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said that the remarks that Japan-U.S. defense
cooperation guidelines would cover the Taiwan Straits has
triggered strong condemnation from China, and is something China
would never tolerate. (DPRK-Japan-Guidelines)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral has strongly
supported enacting a law to prevent criminals from contesting
elections and called for an all-out war against crime and
corruption in politics, the Times of India Saturday today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting in Srinagar, Indian-held Jammu and
Kashmir, Gujral urged political parties to examine the possibility
of state funding of elections to make it more transparent.
</P>
<P>
Political parties in India are currently collecting election
funds by themselves, but the practice has led to rampant
corruption among politicians.(India-PM-Law)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian opposition parties Friday slammed the country's
Prime Minister Romano Prodi for trying to delay the
parliamentary-approved repatriation of some 3,000 Albanian
refugees who fled to Italy earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Leading members of the Freedom Front opposition alliance said
in a joint statement that the government should discuss with the
opposition about the issue before making any decisions that went
beyond the parliamentary approval. (Italy-Albania-Refugee)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIBILISI -- Georgian President Eduard Shervardnadze said Friday
Georgia is highly concerned with the development in China,
praising achievements made in the country's reform.
</P>
<P>
During talks with Wang Bingqian, vice chairman of the Standing
Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress, Shervardnadze
said relations between Georgia and China have developed smoothly
since they established diplomatic ties in 1992.
(China-Georgia-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WARSAW - - Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic said they
would not compete with each other, but cooperate closely, in their
efforts for the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and the
European Union (EU) membership.
</P>
<P>
Polish Prime Minister Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicy and his Hungarian
and Czech counterparts Horn Gyula and Vaclav Klaus made the
remarks Friday after their meeting in Poland's southern city of
Krakov.
</P>
<P>
The three countries are in the first group of nations to join
the NATO. (Poland-Hungary-Czech Republic-Talks) 
</P>
</TEXT>
