<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Scholars Criticize Wolf's Remarks as "Absolutely nonsense"(3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nancy Levine, a professor from the University of California,
said that a policy which takes local conditions into consideration
is being adopted in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
She noted that modernization is reshaping Tibetan people's way
of life. There is no need for people to work 30 days a month
nowadays, residents have more time to travel.
</P>
<P>
"These are good things," she said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Lawrence Epstein, a professor from the University of
Washington, said that since the 1980s, the Tibetan people have
been exploiting their ethnic and natural resources, including
developing tourism, and the local ways of life have been largely
reshaped. At the same time, the process has enhanced the locals'
self-awareness of the Tibetan culture.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that there is a revival of traditional culture in
Tibet and the Chinese government is actively involved in
preserving grottos, paintings and renovating temples," said
Professor Richard Strassberg from the department of East Asian
Languages and Cultures, University of California, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
"I appreciate that there are people who take interests in
preserving the old city of Lhasa," said Dr. Peter Schwieger of the
University of Bonn, Germany, who had been to Tibet and toured 11
towns and villages there since 1986.
</P>
<P>
"I had the impression when I went there last time that there
were positive changes. They now appreciate the cultural history of
Tibet more than before."
</P>
<P>
Dr. Po You Hsing, from the US, said that Tibet has entered a
new era since the mid-20th century, putting an end to the feudal
system of serfdom.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government has allocated a lot of money and sent
many personnel to help improve Tibetan economy...the facts are
known to the whole world," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Tibet was officially incorporated into the
Chinese territory in the 13th century. "The Tibetan people are
members of the Chinese family, and the region is an inseparable
part of China," he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
