<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Increases Taxes to Bridge Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
raised excise on petrol and diesel, rate of value added tax
(VAT), and license fees for vehicles and drivers in a bid to
bridge the budget deficit for the 1997/98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The new revenue measures are expected to earn Kenyan Finance
Ministry an additional 2.8 billion Kenya Shillings (about 43
million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
A legal notice signed by the Finance Minister Musalia Mudavadi
on August 21 said the new tax measures would be complemented with
a further strengthening of tax administration.
</P>
<P>
The main measures include the strengthening of organizational
and operational capacity of the Kenya Revenue Authority and
strict enforcement of maximum compliance with payment of import
duties and VAT.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the notice said, the Kenyan government will
cut non-essential recurrent expenditure and defer development
expenditure for non-priority projects, amounting to a saving of 5
billion Shillings (77 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The implementation of these expenditure control measures will
limit the government's expenditure to 156 billion Shillings
(about 2.4 billion U.S.Dollars) during the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
All these measures are prompted by the recent decision of the
International Monetary Fund to suspend a three-year Enhanced
Structural Adjustment facility to Kenya, of about 205 million
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The expected shortfall for the current budget following the
decision include budget funding amounting to 8.3 billion
Shillings (abut 127.7 million US Dollars) and balance of payments
support totalling 4.4 billion Shillings (67.6 million US
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The notice said that the measures were taken to maintain the
budget deficit at 1.7 percent of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP)
as originally planned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
