<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rain Hits Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- A heavy rain lashed Hong Kong
on Friday and is expected to continue through the weekend before
easing off next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hong Kong Observatory, nearly 160 millimeters
of rainfall was dumped during a four-hour period Friday noon,
triggering widespread flooding, landslides and traffic chaos on
Hong Kong Island, urban Kowloon and the far eastern and western
areas of the "New Territories".
</P>
<P>
There were over 80 reports of flooding, about half of them on
Hong Kong Island including parts of Central District, the
observatory said, adding that the deluge was caused by the outer
rainband of Typhoon Zita as it headed towards the coast of
Guangdong, south China.
</P>
<P>
Friday's downpour brought the total rainfall since the
beginning of the year to 2,878 millimeters, the highest since
records started in 1884, experts here said.
</P>
<P>
The observatory forecast that the rain will continue until next
Tuesday, following the hoisting of the black rainstorm earlier
warning for the second time this year. The black signal was last
hoisted on July 1 when record-breaking rain greeted the historic
handover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
