<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electric Tempos to Appear in Kathmandu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The diesel and petrol-driven
tempos running in this capital city of Nepal will be converted to
electric ones with a view to reducing pollution, Nepali Minister
for Population and Environment Vidya Devi Bhandari said.
</P>
<P>
The Danish organization Danida has donated 25 million rupees
(about 440,000 U.S. dollars) for this purpose, Bhandari said
Friday when answering queries in the Lower House.
</P>
<P>
She said trucks, buses, tempos and other transport vehicles
which have failed the pollution test will be displaced only after
appropriate alternative is explored, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
About 3,600 tempos now are going in the streets of Kathmandu,
which are blamed partly for the deteriorating environment of the
city.
</P>
<P>
However, initially only some of these tempos can be converted
with the fund of 25 million rupees (about 440,000 dollars) after
establishing a small battery charging station, said a press
release issued by the Danish embassy in Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
This initiative came after urgent calls were made from all
walks of life in Kathmandu to start such a program to reduce
pollution before Visit Nepal Year '98 so as to attract more
visitors.
</P>
<P>
Denmark might donate an additional 300 million rupees (about
5.3 million dollars) to convert all diesel-operated tempos in the
Kathmandu Valley, the press release said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
