<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Provides 10.6-Million-Dollar Aid to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Germany has given Zambia 17
million Deutche Marks (about 10.6 million U.S. Dollars) in
technical and project assistance under an agreement signed here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to improve water supply and sanitation,
privatization sector development, agriculture and natural
resources, as well as Germany-funded projects like the Industrial
Training Center (ITC), according to Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Germans as saying the 20 million
Marks (about 12.5 million Dollars) balance of payment support
will be released at the next consultative group meeting to be
held this December if benchmarks of good governance are met.
</P>
<P>
Elin Horn-Vormsschlag, Germany's head of division for southern
Africa, said at the signing ceremony that Germany will continue
to assist Zambia in other sectors like transport, health and
family planning to improve the people's living standard.
</P>
<P>
Ben Mweene, secretary to the Treasury, said on the occasion
that the Zambian government will work hard to ensure projects are
successful.
</P>
<P>
"We are geared to eliminate obstacles in water and sanitation
and to overcome problems of German-funded projects like the ITC,"
said Mweene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
