<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Tourism Receipts Slightly Down in 1st Half of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Total tourism receipts for the
first half of 1997 amounted to 39.8 billion HK dollars (5.14
billion US dollars), down 2.9 percent on the same period last
year, according to figures released today by the Hong Kong Tourist
Association (HKTA).
</P>
<P>
Per capita spending by visitors from all markets, except the
Chinese inland areas, dropped by between 0.5 and 15.6 percent.
Overall, per capita spending was down by 7.8 percent to 6,786 HK
dollars (875.61 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
A HKTA spokesman said that the decline was mostly attributable
to visitor spending from the North Asian region, which showed a
decrease of 25.9 percent to 6.9 billion HK dollars (920 million US
dollars), in line with a slowdown in visitor arrivals from Japan.
</P>
<P>
Visitors from the Americas also spent slightly less, down 3.1
percent to 3.5 billion HK dollars (451 million US dollars), while
visitors from Australia, New Zealand and the South Pacific spent
2.0 percent less at 1.3 billion HK dollars (167 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
But visitors from China' inland areas increased their spending
by 9.7 percent to 8.7 billion HK dollars (1.12 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The HKTA is forecasting a year-end rise in tourism receipts of
about 7 percent to around 90.5 billion HK dollars (11.67 billion
US dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
