<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Exports Most Footballers in the World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Brazil, the sole four-time
champions in the soccer World Cup history, has exported the most
number of footballers throughout the world in the past years.
</P>
<P>
According to the Brazilian Football Association, Brazil has
contributed 2,148 footballers to more than 60 countries and
regions in the past eight and half years.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 326 Brazilian soccer players have flocked to 44
countries and regions in the European, American and Asian
continents in the first six months of the year, which almost
equals the number of players who went abroad in the whole year of
1996.
</P>
<P>
Their main destinations include Portugal, Spain, Japan, Germany
and the United States, while Finland, Indonesia and Macedonia,
where soccer is less developed, also showed strong interest in
importing Brazilian footballers.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilians abroad are believed to be lured by envious
financial benefits as most of them only have a salary of some 600
U.S. dollars at home clubs.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian exports are all welcomed all around the world as
they are adept in individual skills with strong stamina.
</P>
<P>
According to the association, Brazil boasts of a rich pool of
7,238 professional soccer players in the Southern American soccer
kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Negotiate with IMF on Suspended Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is to
resume negotiations with the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
over the key loan suspended three weeks ago, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
President Daniel arap Moi said Friday he had consulted with
IMF managing director who consented to send a mission here next
week for a review of the 215-million-U.S.-Dollar aid cut to the
east African country facing the general election this year.
</P>
<P>
A team from the World Bank and key bilateral and multilateral
donor and aid agencies would also be visiting the country for
similar talks, Moi disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The news sent positive signals to the foreign exchange market
where the Shilling recovered its worst beating in four years to
trade at a commercial mean of 65.85 against the Dollar -- a gain
of 4.6 percent from Thursday's close of 69.1.
</P>
<P>
The Washington-based IMF suspended on August 1 its key loan to
Kenya, citing high-level corruption as a key reason.
</P>
<P>
The aid halt immediately created panic in Kenya's economy with
a three-week downward spiral of the Shilling, although the
Central Bank of Kenya has so far pumped in some 100 million
Dollars sold to commercial banks to stabilize the shock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
