<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines to Cancel 2nd U.S. Route </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL)
announced today that it will cancel its flights to Los Angeles via
Seoul effective from September 1, the second U.S. route the
company was forced to cancel because of the "Category 2" rating
imposed on the Philippines by the United States.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here, PAL said that however, it will
continue to operate its popular non-stop daily flights from Manila
to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, PAL said that it was suspending flights from
Manila to New York starting September 2. The airlines cited
significant losses arising from the effects of the Category 2
ruling on its operations as the reason for pulling out of both the
Manila-Seoul-Los Angeles and the Manila-New York routes.
</P>
<P>
Under the Category 2 rating imposed on the Philippines by the
U.S. Federal Aviation Administration in 1995, any Philippine
carrier is summarily barred from increasing its flights as well as
introducing new services to the United States, unless it uses
aircraft wet-leased from Category 1 Countries, such as the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Wet-leasing an aircraft involves not only the plane itself but
also the flight deck crew. It is a prohibitively expensive deal
because it requires the payment in dollars for the aircraft, crew,
maintenance and insurance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
