<HEADLINE> Mandela's Ex-Wife to Receive Legal Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Winnie Madikizela-Mandela,
ex-wife of the South African President Nelson Mandela, will
appear at a closed inquiry by a special fact-finding group, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Winnie, President of the ruling African National Congress
(ANC) Women's League, is to answer questions of the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) about some murder cases during
the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
A subpoena singed by Dumisa Ntsebeza, head of TRC's
investigative unit, has served on Winnie. However, no date has
been set for the inquiry, the report said.
</P>
<P>
TRC Acting Chairman Alex Boraine, speaking Friday at a press
conference in Cape Town, described Winnie as "a very key person
in the South African political landscape."
</P>
<P>
In another development, Boraine announced that TRC had also
invited former State President P.W. Botha and other former
ministers to testify in October at a special hearing into the
state security policy of the former apartheid government.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Botha too would be subpoenaed if he refuses the
invitation.
</P>
<P>
The coming hearing reportedly would be preceded by an "armed
force public hearing." Members of the former South Africa
defense force, the ANC armed forces, Azanian People's Liberation
Army, the South Africa National Defense Force and the South
Africa police service would be invited. 
</P>
