<HEADLINE> Zambia Adopts New Tourism Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's long-awaited tourism
policy will be launched at the end of this month following a
recent government approval, Zambia Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local paper quoted Deputy Tourism Minister Fidelis Mando
as saying here the new policy will change the approach to tourism
in Zambia because it recognizes the potential of tourism to the
economic development, providing for the participation of private
sector in the management and development of tourism in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"It is based on respect for environment, the habitat, wildlife
and interests of the local communities," Mando said on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Anderson Mazoka, chairman of the Zambia National
Tourist Board (ZNTB) called for the formation of a committee to
market and double the number of tourists visiting Zambia in the
next three years from the current 263,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the special committee comprise the tourism
council, ZNTB and other players in the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Mzaoka said that time has come to stop talking about Zambia's
tourism in terms of potential but to utilize it for the benefit
of all. 
