<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Pollution in Lake Victoria Concerned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Lake Victoria is highly
polluted with over 980 kilograms of industrial waste and some 15
tons of domestic waste deposited annually in it, researchers have
said, according to a report from Arusha, northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The pollution is high near the shores, V. Masanja and N. Mtega,
two academicians of the University of Dar es Salaam, told a
Southern African Mathematical Sciences (SAMSA) symposium in
Arusha on Friday.
</P>
<P>
A news dispatch from the northern Tanzanian town quoted
Masanja and Mtega as saying that they conducted a "mathematical
model", a research based on mathematics, to know the level of
pollution in the lake near Mwanza town and discovered that the
concentration of pollution differs from place to place.
</P>
<P>
Msanja, head of the Mathematics Department of the university,
said lack of treatment facilities and poor on-side sanitation
from domestic activities are major sources of pollution in the
lake.
</P>
<P>
There are in Mwanza town more than 56 industries, generating
effluents per day estimated at 6,500 cubic meters. "Unless
pollution is controlled, Lake Victoria can turn into a curse
instead of a blessing," participants of the symposium observed.
</P>
<P>
Lake Victoria is the largest lake in Africa. It is shared by
Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0152 </DOCNO>
