<HEADLINE> Italian PM's Decision on Albanian Refugees Slammed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Italian opposition parties today
slammed the country's Prime Minister Romano Prodi for trying to
delay the parliamentary-approved repatriation of some 3,000
Albanian refugees who fled to Italy earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Leading members of the Freedom Front opposition alliance
said in a joint statement that the government should discuss with
the opposition about the issue before making any decisions that
went beyond the parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
Until just a few days ago, both Prodi and Interior Minister
Giorgio Napolitano had stood firmly for the parliamentary-approved
decree which fixed August 31 as the deadline for the return of the
Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
However, Prodi announced Thursday that following an appeal by
Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano, he would ask the
government for a delay in the repatriation of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Nano wrote to Prodi, persuading him to take the prevailing
Albanian situation into consideration and not to send back the
refugees immediately after August 31.
</P>
<P>
Terming Prodi's decision as a "surrender," the Italian
opposition alliance said, "There is no tension any longer in
Albania." 
</P>
</TEXT>
