<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CT Scanning Questioned as Heart Attack Predictor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 22 (Xinhua) -- CT scanning cannot predict
heart attacks and death from cardiovascular diseases accurately as
claimed earlier, a team of physicians here said.
</P>
<P>
The team studied 326 middle-aged to elderly people in the Los
Angeles area, using CT scanning for calcium deposits in the
cardio arteries, which had been claimed as an accurate indicator
of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
The results of the study, which was published in the August
issue of the American Heart Association journal "Circulation",
cast doubt on the claim as it was found that even those with
little or no calcium in the cardio arteries can have heart attacks
and die of heart diseases.
</P>
<P>
The team said that the scanning results only predict future
bypass surgery and balloon angioplasty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM Favors New Law to Debar Criminals from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral has strongly supported enacting a law to prevent criminals
from contesting elections and called for an all-out war against
crime and corruption in politics, the Times of India said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting in Srinagar, Indian-held Jammu and
Kashmir, Gujral urged political parties to examine the possibility
of state funding of elections to make it more transparent.
</P>
<P>
Political parties in India are currently collecting election
funds by themselves, but the practice has led to rampant
corruption among politicians.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister suggested that a law should be framed making
it mandatory for contestants to various legislative bodies to
disclose details of whether they were convicted and jailed.
</P>
<P>
This would ensure that criminal elements were kept away from
democratic institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the remarks in reference to the fact
that some corruption-tainted or even jailed politicians have
managed to contest in elections and win.  
</P>
</TEXT>
