<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Georgia Further Improve Friendly Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIBILISI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shervardnadze said today Georgia is highly concerned with the
development in China, praising achievements made in the country's
reform.
</P>
<P>
During talks with Wang Bingqian, vice chairman of the Standing
Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress, Shervardnadze
said relations between Georgia and China have developed smoothly
since they established diplomatic ties in 1992.
</P>
<P>
He said that Georgia paid high tribute to China's foreign
policies, especially that of developing relations with small
countries.
</P>
<P>
Frequent contacts between leaders of the two countries had
established a good basis for bilateral ties and Georgia had had
great support from China since it declared independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the Chinese for support at the United Nations
Security Council meeting on the resumption of Georgia's
territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Sheravrdnadze said that his government would abide by the
principle of "one China" and support China in the Taiwan issue,
adding that Georgia would not seek official contacts with Taiwan
in any form.
</P>
<P>
He also said Hong Kong's return to China has set an example for
resolving territorial problems in other countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shervardnadze suggested that China, whose relations
with the Transcaucasus countries are developing, play a leading
role in holding bilateral or multilateral talks on reactivating
the "Ancient Silk Road."
</P>
<P>
He said the European-Asian corridor would help further improve
the ties between China and Central Asia and Transcaucasus
countries.
</P>
<P>
Wang Bingqian praised the efforts to improve the Sino-Georgian
ties made by Shervardnadze, whose visit to China in June 1993 set
up a solid basis for stable development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed China had been holding the principles of respect
for other countries' sovereignty and independence, saying that the
Abkhazia issue was Georgia's internal affair.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government would support Georgia in its
efforts to protect the state sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
He said China is expecting to see national reunification,
stable politics and economic development in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Wang said China would support Shervardnadze's proposal of
"Peaceful Transcaucasia" which is aimed at resuming and
strengthening the overall cooperation in the Transcaucasus region
as well as jointly safeguarding the regional peace.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Shervardnadze on the preparatory work for the
15th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party, which is an
important event for both China and the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
