<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Gets 3 Months in Jail for Damaging Bernini Fountain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Sebastiano Intili, who damaged the
Bernini fountain in Rome's Plazza Navona, was sentenced today to
three months in prisonment and ordered to pay a fine of
undisclosed amount to the City Council.
</P>
<P>
Intili, 43, broke the tail of a marble sea monster on the
Plazza Navona as he dived off it Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He had also to bear the court expenses of 2 million lire
(1,1120 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The court did not find the two other men who were arrested with
Intili guilty and set them free.
</P>
<P>
The three men were swimming and diving in the water under the
Four Rivers fountain designed by Gian Lorenzo Bernini in
1651. Intili climbed onto one of the four sea monsters and jumped
off, causing the tail to break into three pieces.
</P>
<P>
City officials said that it will cost about 15 million lire
(8,500 dollars) to repair the damage.
</P>
<P>
"It was just a prank, " Intili told a judge Wednesday, "I had
gone out to get a sandwich. I saw the fountain and just felt like
jumping in (from it)."
</P>
<P>
Intili's lawyer, Aldo Ceccarelli, said that his client would
appeal the court decision and ask for compensation from the city
for the hurt on his foot he got when the fountain decoration broke
under him.
</P>
<P>
"I shall ask for 300 million lire (168,000 dollars), "
Ceccarelli said, "not only for the physical damage but also for
the moral damage that my client has suffered." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
