WARSAW, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic said they would not compete, but cooperate closely with
each other in their application for the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and the European Union (EU) membership.
</P>
<P>
Polish Prime Minister Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicy and his Hungarian
and Czech counterparts Horn Gyula and Vaclav Klaus made the
remarks today after their meeting in Poland's southern city of
Krakov.
</P>
<P>
The two-and-half-hour meeting reviewed the preparatory work
already finished and the future negotiations for the membership.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that their government groups responsible for the
matter would cooperate with each other and also exchange views on
the modernization of military forces.
</P>
<P>
Hoping that talks for EU membership could begin early next
year, they planned to meet again next spring.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was their first since NATO decided to invite
them at its July summit in Madrid. Their foreign and defense
ministers met in July in Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski met with
Horn and Klaus this afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
