<HEADLINE> U.S. Approves Pilgrimage to Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration today
approved a request from the Archdiocese of Miami to sail a cruise
ship to Cuba taking Catholics to see Pope John Paul II when he
visits Cuba in next January.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, State Department spokesman James Rubin said
this was the only license so far approved for travel to Cuba for
the pope's five-day visit starting on January 20.
</P>
<P>
The license granted by the Treasury's Office of Foreign Assets
Control would permit pilgrims to spend limited amounts of money in
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration imposed the embargo in 1963 banning all
commerce with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that other requests would be considered on a
case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
Americans trying to visit Cuba have to go via third countries.
The cruise planned by the Miami Archdiocese will allow pilgrims to
travel directly from the United States to Cuba. 
</P>
