<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean Fish Catch Drops Over Seven Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chilean fish catch stood at
4.587 million tons in the first seven months of this year, a 14.1
percent decrease over the same period last year, fishing
authorities said here today.
</P>
<P>
Although the capture of anchovy increased 42.6 percent and
common sardines 41.1 percent from January to July, they could not
offset the 36.3 percent drop in the capture of yellow jacket
during the period.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino phenomenon, an abnormal meteorological happening,
had a negative impact on the survival of fingerlings and ova,
resulting in the future captures drop, the sources warned.
</P>
<P>
Chilean fish exports in the first half of the year earned 935.5
million U.S. dollars, a 4.6 percent increase over the same period
of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Exports of fishing products reached 1.772 billion dollars in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
