<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Province Pushes Full Steam Ahead on Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong province's foreign
trade witnessed a balanced development in the January-July period,
today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Exports progressed rapidly and imports rose steadily, a report
from Guangdong Customs Office revealed.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign trade value rose 22.2 percent from a year ago to
surpass 69.4 billion US dollars in the first seven months.
</P>
<P>
Exports rocketed 32.2 percent to exceed 39.9 billion US
dollars, while imports edged up 10.9 percent to 29.5 billion US
dollars. That created a 10.42 billion US dollars trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
Customs official Lin Jianpin noted the government's efforts to
alleviate the pressure on foreign trade enterprises by
accelerating tax rebates was one reason exports in the sector grew
so rapidly.
</P>
<P>
Imports and exports through the processing trade were worth
about 50.5 billion US dollars, up 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports rose 17.8 percent, surpassing 29.2 billion US dollars
and imports rose 16 percent to about 21.3 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
State-run enterprises grew faster in both imports and exports
than foreign-invested enterprises, the report said.
</P>
<P>
State-run enterprises' imports and exports gained 30.2 percent
to be worth more than 30.4 billion US dollars, while
foreign-invested enterprises rose 16.4 percent to be worth more
than 36.9 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report said most trade was done with Asian countries and
regions, including Honk Kong, Japan, Taiwan, South Korea and
Singapore, as well as the United States and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Honk Kong were the largest, with the total value
notching up 16.2 billion, accounting for 40.2 percent of exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
