<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Honduras' Archbishop Refuses To Command Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Oscar Rodriguez, archbishop
of Tegucigalpa and president of the Latin American Bishops Council
(CELAM), refused today to assume the command of the new civilian
police of Honduras.
</P>
<P>
The Honduras Congress Tuesday approved the appointment of
Rodriguez as the chief of a national board overseeing the
transformation of the Honduran police.
</P>
<P>
Clergyman Pedro Drowing, general vicar of the Tegucigalpa
archdiocese and spokesman for Rodriguez, said that the archbishop
was not consulted before being appointed to the post.
</P>
<P>
The post of national police chief cannot be performed
simultaneously with his mission as the leader of the Honduras
Catholic Church, Drowing said.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez has gone to Houston, the United States, for a medical
checkup and he will return Monday to Tegucigalpa.
</P>
<P>
Vatican delegate in Honduras, Luigi Conti, said that Pope John
Paul II would not permit the CELAM head to be a police chief.
</P>
<P>
Canon law forbids clergymen to occupy government posts without
Vatican license. A similar limitation is established in the
Honduran constitution for all clergymen.
</P>
<P>
Archbishop Rodriguez, 55 and a priest for 27 years, was elected
CELAM president in 1995 for a four-year term.
</P>
<P>
The Honduran Congress amended the Constitution in last December
to transfer police, which in the past 33 years has been controlled
by the military, to the civilian power.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of the archbishop to command the Honduran
police has caused controversy since some consider it illegal and
other see it as a way to facilitate the transition of the military
command to civilian dominion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Relations Need New Spirit, Goal: Soeharto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
said international relations need a new spirit and goal, namely,
partnership to attain progress, welfare and safety for all.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks here Friday night in his speech
at a state banquet in honor of visiting Zambian President Fredrick
Jacob Titus Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto said Indonesia and Zambia as Non-Aligned Movement
(NAM) members were obliged to constantly strive to create a new
order in the world that was more just and more responsible.
</P>
<P>
North-South cooperation was inevitable, he said, adding that in
the current era, all countries both the big and the small, the
rich and the poor, and the developed and the developing ones,
depended on each other.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto expressed his confidence that countries despite their
small capabilities would be powerful if they integrated into one
for the good of all.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, Indonesia and Zambia had an
opportunity to enhance their bilateral economic cooperation
despite the current small trade volume between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that the end of the cold war and the globalization had
caused the world to become freer and increasingly open in which
all nations had new opportunities to jointly create more peace,
welfare and justice in the world.
</P>
<P>
To materialize such a condition, it was important to enhance
South-South cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president, who arrived here Thursday for a four-day
state visit, held talks with Soeharto early Friday on developing
bilateral economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba is scheduled to leave here for Singapore Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
