<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Cabinet Swears in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Valeriy
Pustovoitenko finally finished forming his new government as
it took an oath of office today.
</P>
<P>
At the swearing ceremony at the Mariynsky Palace -- the
presidential palace -- Pustovoitenko said the main task of the new
cabinet is to deepen the nation's social and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko has appointed four deputy prime ministers and 47
ministers for his new cabinet since he replaced the fired Prime
Minister Pavel Lazarenko on July 16.
</P>
<P>
Addressing members of the new cabinet, Ukrainian President
Leonid Kuchma said the cabinet must assume full and absolute
responsibility since it is the highest organ of the executive
branch of government.
</P>
<P>
"The government's main task is to revive and stabilize the
economy and create necessary conditions for its growth," said
Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for the government to give regular radio
and television reports of its activities.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary Speaker Alexander Moroz said at the occasion that
the new cabinet stands the chance of making history as it will
achieve positive development in all spheres of public life.
</P>
<P>
"The parliament aims to engage in constructive cooperation with
the Cabinet of Ministers," concluded Moroz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
