<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Aims for Better Art Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- China will make more efforts to
enhance aesthetic education among the country's primary and middle
schools starting this year, today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
Turning the current examination-dominated education mode into a
quality-oriented one has aroused great attention in educational
circles in China, the paper quoted Liu Bin, vice-minister of the
State Education Commission (SEC), as saying.
</P>
<P>
Liu added that aesthetic education plays a vital role in
fostering students' morality and interests.
</P>
<P>
Starting this year, according to Liu, the SEC will set up art
lecture groups comprising aesthetic experts to train art teachers
among schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
On a conference marking the establishment of the groups
yesterday, 200 Chinese primary and middle school teachers of
aesthetic subjects received awards for their excellent work - the
first time that has happened since the People's Republic of China
was founded in 1949, said Liu.
</P>
<P>
The SEC has mapped out its plan for developing aesthetic
education over the next few years, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
By the end of next year, a national network will be set up
focusing on teaching guidance for aesthetic education among
schools.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, all schools in regions that have popularized the
nine-year compulsory education are required to offer music and art
courses, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the state should also increase funding for
aesthetic education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
