<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0040 GMT, August 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Over 107 refugees have been massacred and 30 others
wounded in a raid on a camp housing ethnic Tutsis from former
Zaire in Gisenyi, a town at Rwanda's northwestern border, the
U.N. refugee agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Pamela O'toole, spokeswoman of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNCHR), said preliminary reports showed that the ethnic
Tutsis, who fled fighting in the Masisi region of the former
Zaire, were slaughtered with machetes by unidentified attackers
late on Thursday night. (Rwanda-Massacre)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- Zimbabwe and Denmark Friday signed a 2.3 million
U.S. Dollars agreement which will fund the Southern African
regional peace-keeping training center.
</P>
<P>
The money would be used to build infrastructure at the Zimbabwe
military staff college which houses the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) regional center for peace-keeping
studies, and develop training programs. (Zimbabwe-Denmark-Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The area of wetlands around Mai Po and Inner Deep
Bay in Hong Kong has become China's seventh Wetland of
International Importance under the Ramsar Convention.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the convention, every signatory country is
obliged to guarantee the wise use and conservation of its wetlands
in a bid to protect the rich fauna and flora that they
support. (China-Wetland)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng said Friday
China attaches importance to the active role played by the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in the regional
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The enlargement of ASEAN conforms with the development trend of
global multi-polarization and is conducive to peace and
development in the Asia-Pacific region, Li said during his talks
with Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohammad. (China-Malaysia-ASEAN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin met 11 journalists in
the Kremlin Friday who were rescued recently after being held
hostage in Chechnya for months, the Itar-Tass News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Russian Federal Security Service played a key
role in rescuing the journalists.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he praised the journalists, who were from Public
Russian Television, Independent Television and other news media,
for having displayed courage and endurance while being
held. (Yeltsin-Journalists) 
