<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Angry Over U.S. Anti-Immigrant Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Mexico is strongly opposing
new anti-immigration actions being taken by the United States
along its border with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Mexican diplomatic sources said here today that Mexican Foreign
Minister Jose Angel Gurria has sent two notes to the
U.S. government over the actions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) announced
last week that from August 25, it would expand the first phase of
"Operation Rio Grande" between the U.S. city of Brownsville,
Texas, and the Mexican city of Matamoros, Tamaulipas.
</P>
<P>
The operation, aimed at "sealing" the border to prevent the
crossing of illegal immigrants, has been supported by a
considerable increase in the number of border agents (69 in the
first stage), and use of the most advanced military technology to
detect people illegally crossing at any time of the day.
</P>
<P>
In its notes, Mexico expressed concern over the recruitment of
a great number of inexperienced agents by the U.S. border patrol
for anti-immigration operations.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican government said it was worried that these agents
lacked the necessary experience to perform anti-immigration work,
and they would trigger "an international incident between Mexico
and the United States."
</P>
<P>
The president of the College of the Northern Border, Jorge A.
Bustamante, said the aim of the expansion of U.S. anti-immigrant
operations was to palliate the dissatisfaction -- caused by the
U.S. military withdrawal along its border -- among those who
demanded a tougher immigration policy toward Mexico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
