<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sandinistas, Government to Sign Document on Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Nicaraguan government and
the National Liberation Sandinista Front (FSLN) have agreed to
sign a law project on property next week to rid the country of a
major factor which often causes political instability.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Julio Centeno Gomez said, "I estimate that the
law project will be ready in four or five days to be submitted to
the persons who lead the policies in this matter for
consideration."
</P>
<P>
Centeno was quoted today by the "Nuevo Diario" newspaper as
saying that the document was drafted by the juridical
subcommission which President Arnoldo Aleman and Sandinista leader
Daniel Ortega created in February.
</P>
<P>
The subcommission comprises lawyers of the government and the FSLN,
the main opposition in the country.
</P>
<P>
The problem of property has been one of the biggest factors
which frequently lead to bloodshed and political instability in
Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
When the Sandinistas ruled the country, they confiscated the
properties of the Somoza government officials and National Guard
officers through what was known as Decree 38, which the FSLN agreed
to annul now.
</P>
<P>
The proposed project, which has more than 70 articles, will
"benefit only the subjects of the social reform, those persons who
are qualified by the laws 85, 86 and 88," said Centeno.
</P>
<P>
Centeno said the project does not cover the properties in the
hands of Sandinista leaders and of the firms privatized by the
Public Sector National Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Both sides considered that the Somoza family assets must not be
returned.
</P>
<P>
The project must be sent to the forum known as the National
Dialogue, where it is supposed to be subject to the "test of fire"
because there is resistance from a section of the government to
establish a political accord with the Sandinistas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
