<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two World Marks Fall at Belgian Athletics Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Two Kenyans shattered as many
world records at the annual Memorial Van Damme track and field
event, the third stop on the IAAF Grand Prix Golden Four circuit
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Komen went it alone on the way to clock a world record
time of 12 minutes 39.74 seconds in the 5,000 meters, beating the
10-day-old world mark of 12:41.86.
</P>
<P>
The previous mark was set by Haile Gebrelassie from Ethiopia at
the Zurich Grand Prix which was the second Golden Four event.
Komen asked race organizers to add the event to the Belgian meet.
</P>
<P>
Though Komen was the lonesome runner for most of the race, an
encouraging and appreciating crowd cheered him on and on.
</P>
<P>
Paul Tergat was second for most of the 10,000-meter race. He
overtook compatriot and pace-setter Paul Koech with two laps to go
and kicked home with the day's second world record.
</P>
<P>
His time of 26:27.85 was more than three seconds faster than
the world record time Gebrelassie clocked at the opening event of
the Golden Four in Oslo of Norway on July 4.
</P>
<P>
Tergat had two minutes for the last kilometer to beat the world
mark and he was cheered on by a capacity crowd that turned out on
the weekend after a morning drizzle and a whole day of overcast
cooled local temperatures.
</P>
<P>
"I just knew I was going to break that world record today in
Brussels," said a delighted Komen at the post-race briefing. "It
was in the air all night and even before going into the last
kilometer, I had the feeling that nothing could go wrong."
</P>
<P>
He said that he only expected Gebrelassie to better his record
again. "At this moment I see only one athlete who can break this
one and it's of course Gebrelassie."
</P>
<P>
The world record setter attributed the win to the spectators
and promised to come back next year.
</P>
<P>
Three more athletes had something else to celebrate from the
night.
</P>
<P>
Frankie Fredericks of Namibia, Gabriela Szabo of Romania and
Hicham el Guerrouj of Morocco all scored consecutive third
triumphs on the Golden Four circuit, winning their respective
disciplines.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian, a disappointing fourth-place finisher at the
Athens Worlds, beat newly-crowned world champion Maurice Greene of
the United States again in the 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
Fredericks scored a meet record of 9.90 seconds to win his
third Golden Four event, moving a step closer to sharing the
jackpot of 20 kilograms of gold offered by the circuit organizers.
</P>
<P>
The fourth and last stop of the Golden Four event will be held
in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
"I'm proud of the fact that I can run good races during the
whole of the season," said 29-year-old Fredericks. "And it is
always fantastic to beat the world champion."
</P>
<P>
The Namibian sprinter said that today's win kept him in the
race for the Golden Four title.
</P>
<P>
Szabo overtook early leader Paula Radcliffe of Britain with 250
meters to go and sped home for the win which also kept her in the
race for the Golden Four title
</P>
<P>
Her time of 14:44.21 was also a meet record.
</P>
<P>
El Guerrouj kicked off only at the bell and never looked back
to tighten his grip over the Golden Four title. He won the
1,500-meter event on 3:28.92, still another meet record to fall on
the fast track in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Entering today's meet, there were three others who could be
candidates for the gold bullions. Yet off-form performance ended
their winning streaks.
</P>
<P>
Trine Hattestad of Norway, who won the Oslo and Zurich events,
fouled twice and tossed a 58.52-meter distance before pulling out
of the women's javelin throw. She finished ninth out of nine
competitors.
</P>
<P>
Deon Hemmings of Jamaica was beaten by Kim Batten of the United
States in the women's 400-meter hurdles while Allen Johnson of the
United States also lost his chance of chasing the gold as he was
defeated in the 110-meter hurdles by countryman Mark Crear with a
clocking of 13.20.
</P>
<P>
Wilson Boit Kipketer of Kenya, a world record setter at the
Zurich grand prix event, was unlucky when he was on a fast pace
and leading the 3,000-meter steeplechase. He lost balance jumping
off the last pool, only to give the lead to another Kenyan runner,
Moses Kiptanui, who won the race on 8:05.35.
</P>
<P>
A total of 24 current world champions and 16 Atlanta Olympic
titlists participated in today's meet.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meet, American sprinter and long jumper Carl
Lewis, winner of nine Olympic gold medals, bid farewell to the
Brussels stop of the IAAF Grand Prix circuit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
