<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dry-up Period Ended in Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 23 (Xinhua) -- This year's second round of
flooding washed over the Yellow River early this morning, ending
the seventh dry spell in the lower reaches of China's second
longest river.
</P>
<P>
Heavy flooding occurred in early August, ending the drought that
wreaked havoc on east China's Shandong Province for months. Huge
water demands along the riverbanks, however, soon dried up the
river again.
</P>
<P>
Major cities along the river, in particular those at the upper
or middle reaches, were setting water-use quotas so as to ensure
the supply of water in the lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said that efforts were to continue on water
resource management even though the waterflow had resumed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970823.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealanders Paid More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Salaries and wages in New
Zealand rose 2.5 percent in the year to June 1977, the biggest
annual increase in six years, Statistics NZ said today.
</P>
<P>
A big increase in teachers' salaries has contributed to the pay
rise. On average, a teacher now earns 6.5 percent more than one
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Apart from teaching professionals, Salary and wage rates being
paid in the public sector rose 3.3 percent in the year, compared
with 2.2 percent for the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Central government services had the highest industry group
increase in salary and wage rates in the year, rising 3.7 percent,
Statistics NZ said.
</P>
<P>
But manufacturing, an industry hit by poor performance in the
past year, recorded a lower-than-average annual increase of 2.1
percent, the office said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
